{"title_page": "Clarity (Jimmy Eat World album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Clarity\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jimmy Eat World]]\n| cover      = Clarity.jpeg\n| alt        = A 2x2 image of 4 different photographs, including inside a body, red fingerprints, light, and the ocean. The words \"JIMMY EAT WORLD.CLARITY\" can be seen along with the image. The big word \"CLARITY.\" can be seen on the left of the image.\n| released   = {{start date|1999|02|23}}\n| recorded   = 1998\u20131999\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Sound City and Clear Lake Audio ([[Los Angeles]])\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[emo]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[indie rock]]\n* [[punk rock]]\n}}<!--All the genres are cited within the \"Reception and legacy\" section-->\n| length     = 64:22\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| producer   = [[Mark Trombino]]\n| prev_title = [[Static Prevails]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Singles (Jimmy Eat World album)|Singles]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Clarity\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Lucky Denver Mint\n | single1date = January 1, 1999\n | single2     = Blister\n | single2date = July 19, 1999\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Clarity''''' (stylized as '''''.CLARITY''''' and '''''CLARITY.''''') is the third studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Jimmy Eat World]], released on February 23, 1999, by [[Capitol Records]]. Overlooked upon its release, ''Clarity'' has since amassed [[cult status]] and critical acclaim, and has been lauded as one of the best [[emo music|emo records]] of all time.<ref name=\"RS1\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/40-greatest-emo-albums-of-all-time-20160301/jimmy-eat-world-clarity-1999-20160225 |title= 40 Greatest Emo Albums of All Time, #13|magazine=[[Rolling Stone Magazine]]|author=Bayer, Jonah|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"PNT2\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com/uponsun/2009/03/jimmy_eat_worlds_clarity_anniv.php |title= Jimmy Eat World's Clarity Anniversary Show Impressive|website=[[The Phoenix New Times]]|author=Cizmar, Martin|date=8 March 2009|accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref> Praise centered on its dynamic [[instrumentation]], as well as the heartfelt delivery of singer-guitarist-lyricist [[Jim Adkins]]. Various music critics have credited the album for serving as a huge influence on later emo music.<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com/uponsun/2008/11/jimmy_eat_world_celebrates_ann.php |title=Jimmy Eat World Celebrates Anniversary of Clarity By Playing It Live|author=Cizmar, Martin|website=[[The Phoenix New Times]]|date=10 November 2008|accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Spin1\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/jimmy-eat-world-celebrate-10-years-clarity?page=0%2C1 |title=Jimmy Eat World Celebrate 10 Years of 'Clarity'|author=Gaston, Peter|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=24 February 2009|accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"HWI\">{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodiconmagazine.com/2009/03/10/jimmy-eat-world-celebrate-a-decade-of-%E2%80%9Cclarity%E2%80%9D-in-la/|title=Jimmy Eat World Celebrate a Decade of \"Clarity\" in LA|publisher=Hollywood Icon|date=10 March 2009|accessdate=22 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817234348/http://hollywoodiconmagazine.com/2009/03/10/jimmy-eat-world-celebrate-a-decade-of-%E2%80%9Cclarity%E2%80%9D-in-la/|archivedate=17 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\nDuring breaks in touring in support of ''Static Prevails'', Adkins worked at an art store. While working at this store, \"Table for Glasses\" came about.<ref name=trackbytrack>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmyeatworld.com/clarity/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716202344/http://www.jimmyeatworld.com/clarity/|title=CLARITY TRACK BY TRACK|archivedate=16 July 2009|work=jimmyeatworld.com|accessdate=17 May 2015}}</ref> Adkins learned about shows that featured art pieces from local artists.<ref name=trackbytrack/> Adkins was waiting for a friend's piece to begin when he spotted a girl clearing the area with the end of her dress.<ref name=trackbytrack/> The girl walked towards \"a candle lit table that had already been set up. She just sat there picking out the dirt from her dress\", recalls Adkins.<ref name=trackbytrack/> \"Table for Glasses\" was one of a few songs that was intended for \"a side project of quiet songs\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> The project never got beyond jamming, and thus the songs were considered for ''Clarity''.<ref name=trackbytrack/> \"Lucky Denver Mint\" was inspired by a night out in Las Vegas Adkins had with a friend.<ref name=McMahon19>McMahon, ed. 2015, p. 19</ref> Adkins was too young to consume alcohol and instead gambled, eventually spending all of his money.<ref name=McMahon19/> As a result, Adkins spent the remainder of the night \"walking around feeling lost.\"<ref name=McMahon19/>\n\n\"Your New Aesthetic\" was originally a \"very mellow\" song, but was turned into \"a more aggressive, dark rock song\", as Lind notes.<ref name=trackbytrack/> This version was named \"Skeleton\" as the guitar sections between the verses \"reminded us of horror film music\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> It featured different lyrics but Adkins thought he could improve upon them and changed the lyrics from the mellow version.<ref name=trackbytrack/>\n\nThe lyrics for \"Goodbye Sky Harbor\" were based on the John Irving novel ''[[A Prayer for Owen Meany]]''.<ref name=COS>{{cite web|author=Ben Kaye |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/06/dissected-jimmy-eat-world-with-jim-adkins/4/|title=Dissected: Jimmy Eat World (with Jim Adkins)|work=Consequence of Sound|page=4|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Recording==\n{{quote box|quote= The atmosphere of the Clarity sessions was very encouraging for experimentation. Any idea was explored for some element to make the song better. I would think a song was totally finished and then one of the guys in the band or [producer] Mark [Trombino] would bring up an idea that really closed the deal.<ref name=trackbytrack/>|source= \u2013 Jim Adkins, on the recording sessions for ''Clarity'', 2009|width=25%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}\nOn recording \"Table for Glasses\", Adkins said the band learned \"if you aren't doing a lot, it doesn't take a lot to get a big dynamic impact\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> Adkins noted the cello was \"a good example of that\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> Susie Katayama provided Adkins assistance in writing and arranging the string parts for some of the songs.<ref name=trackbytrack/> The band recorded two different drum sets on \"Lucky Denver Mint\", a first for the band.<ref name=trackbytrack/> They had liked the effect, and as a result, used two sets on \"Ten\" and \"Goodbye Sky Harbor\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> The album was recorded in late 1998 to early 1999 at Sound City and Clear Lake Audio, both in [[North Hollywood]], with the tracks' mixing occurring at One on One in [[Los Angeles]] and Bernie Grundman Mastering in Hollywood.<ref name=\"AltPress2\"/>\n\n''Clarity'' marks the start of Jim Adkins - as opposed to Tom Linton - providing lead vocals. With the exception of the song \"Blister\" and \"Your New Aesthetic,\" Tom from this point on only provided backing vocals on various tracks until 2010's \"Action Needs an Audience\" off their album ''Invented''.<ref>{{cite web |author=Justin Gerber|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/06/dissected-jimmy-eat-world-with-jim-adkins/8/|title=Dissected: Jimmy Eat World (with Jim Adkins)|work=Consequence of Sound|page=8|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nAdkins revealed that despite the fact the album was \"complete\", it had no immediate release date.<ref name=trackbytrack/> The group's A&R guy suggested an EP with a few more songs.<ref name=trackbytrack/> [[Vinnie Fiorello]] of [[Less Than Jake]], who ran the label [[Fueled by Ramen]], was contacted and supported the idea.<ref name=trackbytrack/> The ''Jimmy Eat World'' EP was released by Fueled by Ramen<ref name=NWAHM182>Sharpe-Young 2005, p. 182</ref> on December 14, 1998<ref name=JEWEP>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmyeatworld.com/discography/detail.aspx?pid=393|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806222522/http://www.jimmyeatworld.com/discography/detail.aspx?pid=393|title=Jimmy Eat World|archivedate=6 August 2012|work=jimmyeatworld.com|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> and featured two songs from ''Clarity'': \"Lucky Denver Mint\" and \"For Me This Is Heaven\".{{#tag:ref|U.S. Fueled by Ramen FBR020<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fueledbyramen.com/releases/index.php?id=020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030808154417/http://www.fueledbyramen.com/releases/index.php?id=020|title=Fueled By Ramen - Releases|archivedate=8 August 2003|work=fueledbyramen.com|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} Los Angeles-based radio station KROQ picked up on \"Lucky Denver Mint\",<ref name=NWAHM182/> which resulted in a big interest in the song that gained it a place in the [[Drew Barrymore]] film ''[[Never Been Kissed]]''.<ref name=NWAHM182/> After this, the band was given a release date for the album.<ref name=trackbytrack/> Adkins had a \"strong suspicion\" that the production staff was purposely \"keeping from us that the label had no intention of releasing ''Clarity''\", prior to the airplay from KROQ.<ref name=trackbytrack/> Adkins said that major labels were good at selling large sums of albums but did not have the \"infrastructure to develop a band like us\".<ref name=trackbytrack/>\n\n''Clarity'' was released by [[Capitol Records]] on February 23, 1999.{{#tag:ref|U.S. Capitol CDP 7243 8 55950 2 8|group=\"nb\"}} However, despite critical praise and promotion of \"Lucky Denver Mint\" in the film ''[[Never Been Kissed]]'', ''Clarity'' was commercially unsuccessful in a musical climate dominated by [[teen pop]], and the band was dropped from Capitol Records the following year.<ref name=\"Greenwald, 103-104\">Greenwald, pp. 103\u2013104.</ref>\n\nAfter being dropped by Capitol, the band used this time to undertake extensive touring which allowed them to self-fund recording sessions for their eventual mainstream breakthrough, ''[[Bleed American]]'' (2001).<ref name=\"AP\"/> \n\nAlong with ''[[Static Prevails]]'' (1996), the album was re-released on May 15, 2007. The reissue included \"Christmas Card\" and a studio demo of \"Sweetness\" as bonus tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1516|title=AP Exclusive: Jimmy Eat World to reissue first two albums|work=Alternative Press|date=November 16, 2006|accessdate=August 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822204033/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1516|archive-date=August 22, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Two years later, the band released ''[[Clarity Live]]'' (2009), recorded during its commemorative tenth anniversary tour.\n\nThe 2009 vinyl re-release package included the two new bonus tracks as well as a ''Clarity 2009'' tour T-shirt. The 16 pictures used on the album's cover were shot by Paul Drake, Crissy Piper and J Gnewikow. For the 2009 re-issue, all 16 images appear on the front of the record. Art company The Uprising were hired to re-work the art for the 2009 release, using the original images, saying, \"...we were brought on to reconstruct and reinterpret the original artwork. We wanted to stay true to the original, but give it a slightly more sophisticated and updated look & feel. These reconstructions are always a little tricky because you rarely get all of the original art assets you need, but this turned out fantastic. And the actual prints look amazing!\".<ref>[http://www.theuprisingintl.com/blog/2009/01/22/jimmy-eat-world-10th-anniversary-limited-edition-clarity-vinyl-reissue/ Jimmy Eat World - 10th Anniversary Limited Edition Clarity Vinyl Reissue] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408205121/http://www.theuprisingintl.com/blog/2009/01/22/jimmy-eat-world-10th-anniversary-limited-edition-clarity-vinyl-reissue/ |date=2009-04-08 }} The Uprising, January 22, 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.chrissypiper.com/index.html chrissypiper] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228074159/http://www.chrissypiper.com/index.html |date=2009-02-28 }} Chrissy Piper, Clarity photographer, February 2009</ref>\n\n==Clarity x 10 Tour==\nThe 2009 U.S. ''Clarity x 10'' Tour, celebrating the 10th anniversary of ''Clarity'', was announced in November 2008 and went across 10 dates in 10 different states. The tour opened on February 23rd, 2009, at Terminal 5 in [[New York City|New York]], with shows on February 24th in [[Washington, D.C.]], February 25th in Trocadero Theater in [[Philadelphia]], February 26th at the [[House of Blues]] in [[Boston]], February 28th at the [[Metro Chicago|Metro]] in [[Chicago]], March 2nd at the Ogden Theater in [[Denver]], March 4th at The Fillmore in [[San Francisco]], March 5th at [[Club Nokia]] in [[Los Angeles]], and March 6th at [[San Diego]]'s House of Blues, before finally ending in the band's home state of Arizona on March 7th at the Marquee Theatre in [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]]. Support for the tour came from No Knife and Reuben's Accomplice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://intunemusiconline.com/2009/03/24/jimmy-eat-world-reubens-accomplice-nyc-223/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120605020520/http://intunemusiconline.com/2009/03/24/jimmy-eat-world-reubens-accomplice-nyc-223/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-06-05 |title=inTuneMusic Online: Jimmy Eat World Clarity Tour |accessdate=2009-03-24 |author=Ambrose, Anthony |date=2009-03-24 }}</ref> The band, who had been extensively rehearsing in-studio, performed a rehearsal live over the internet on February 12th, 2009. The band also been used the [[social network]] [[Twitter]] to update and share photos and other material from the studio.<ref name=\"NME4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/jimmy-eat-world/40965 |title= Jimmy Eat World announce 'Clarity' tour. The 10 shows will see band play 1999 album in its entirety |work=[[NME]]|author=Staff|date=10 November 2008|accessdate=11 November 2008}}</ref> The band released ''[[Clarity Live]]'' - a digital-only release of the ''Clarity x 10'' tour's finale, recorded in Tempe - on April 7, 2009.<ref name=\"NME2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/jimmy-eat-world/43191 |title= Jimmy Eat World to release 'Clarity Live' |work=[[NME]]|author=Staff|date=4 March 2009|accessdate=5 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n{{Album ratings\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/clarity-mw0000602620 |title= ''Clarity'' \u2013 Jimmy Eat World|website=[[AllMusic]]|author=Vanderhoff, Mark|accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"AltPress\">{{Citation | title = Jimmy Eat World: ''Clarity'' (Capitol)| newspaper = [[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] | date = February 1999|author=Heisel, Scott|issue=124|page=45|issn = 1065-1667}}<!--|accessdate=11 September 2003--></ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Blender\">{{Citation | title = Jimmy Eat World: ''Clarity'' (Capitol)| newspaper = [[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] | date = July 2007|author=Greenwald, Andy|issn = 1534-0554|authorlink = Andy Greenwald|issue=60}}<!--|accessdate=11 July 2007--></ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev4Score = 5/5<ref name=\"Kerr Review\">{{Citation | title = Jimmy Eat World: ''Clarity'' (Capitol)| newspaper = [[Kerrang!]] | date = February 1999|author=Brannigan, Paul|issue=795|page=49}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev5Score = 3.5/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/18878-clarity|title=Jimmy Eat World: ''Clarity''|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=16 May 2010|last=DiCrescenzo|first=Brent|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603120738/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/18878-clarity|archivedate=3 June 2008}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Record Collector]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"RC\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.recordcollectormag.com/reviews/review-detail/1380 |title=Jimmy Eat World \u2013 ''Clarity''|journal=[[Record Collector]]|author=Goodman, Eleanor|issue=342|date=November 2007|accessdate=16 May 2010}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Jimmy Eat World|last=Ryan|first=Chris|title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|edition=4th|year=2004|isbn=0-7432-0169-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/432 432]|title-link=The Rolling Stone Album Guide}}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[RT\u00c9 Entertainment]]\n| rev8Score= {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"RTE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2002/0910/jimmyeatworldalbums.html |title=Jimmy Eat World \u2013 ''Clarity''|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Entertainment]]|author=Guerin, Harry |date=9 August 2007|accessdate=16 May 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107102327/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2002/0910/jimmyeatworldalbums.html|archivedate=7 November 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev9Score = 4.5/5<ref name=\"Sputnik\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sputnikmusic.com/album.php?albumid=453|title=Jimmy Eat World: Clarity|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|author=Hartwig, Andrew|date=17 September 2005|accessdate=13 November 2009}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Stylus Magazine]]''\n| rev10Score = A<ref name=\"Stylus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/jimmy-eat-world/clarity.htm |title=Jimmy Eat World \u2013 ''Clarity'' \u2013 Review |work=[[Stylus Magazine]] |author=Merwin, Charles |date=9 August 2007 |accessdate=16 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503053050/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/jimmy-eat-world/clarity.htm |archivedate=3 May 2010 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nDespite being largely overlooked upon its release, the album's critical stature has grown in time. A contemporaneous review of ''Clarity'' by ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' was dismissive of the album.<ref name=\"pitchfork\"/> In retrospect, the album is now viewed as a \"masterpiece\", a \"landmark album of the 1990s\", and \"the ''[[Led Zeppelin IV]]'' of emo rock\".<ref name=\"Spin1\"/><ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web|url=http://absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?p=37646582#post=37646582 |title= Jimmy Eat World \u2013 Clarity Live|website=[[AbsolutePunk]]|author=Tate, Jason|date=3 March 2009|accessdate=4 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"RTE\"/> In 2008, ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine polled members of seventeen modern-day bands, all of whom cited [[Jim Adkins]]\u2019 writing and performance on the record as a primary influence.<ref name=\"Hip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hiponline.com/6261/jimmy-eat-world-announce-clarity-tour.html|title=Jimmy Eat World announce Clarity tour|publisher=Hip Online|accessdate=10 November 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121231072207/http://www.hiponline.com/6261/jimmy-eat-world-announce-clarity-tour.html|archivedate=31 December 2012}}</ref> Similarly, [[Manchester Orchestra]] bassist Jonathan Corley, in an interview with ''[[Rip It Up (magazine)|Rip it Up]]'' magazine, said that ''Clarity'' was one of his all-time favourite records and one that \"changed the way I look at music.\"<ref name=\"RIU\">{{cite web|url=http://ripitup.co.nz/contentitem/interview-manchester-orchestra/852 |title=Interview \u2013 Manchester Orchestra |publisher=[[Rip It Up (magazine)|Rip it Up]] |date=9 September 2010 |accessdate=23 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129050513/http://ripitup.co.nz/contentitem/interview-manchester-orchestra/852 |archivedate=29 November 2010 }}</ref> Preceding the band's tenth anniversary tour of the album, Pete Cottell of the ''[[Phoenix New Times]]'' wrote, \"What's truly admirable about the album is that it moves in so many different directions without getting lost on its journey. There's a tirade against shameless conformity (\"Your New Aesthetic\"), a herky-jerky, post-punk Police homage (\"Believe in What You Want\"), and a shimmering power ballad (\"For Me This Is Heaven\"). While (\"Goodbye Sky Harbor\") spills over with layered harmonies, chiming guitar passages, and 808 spurt. Unlike the 12 other tracks on ''Clarity'', it's an almost impossible undertaking upon first listen. Once you've made it to the 13-minute mark, however, you'll never hit the skip button again.\" Cottell also stated \"I intently listened to each of the 13 tracks, fearing I would be let down by yet another alt-rock album that had little to offer besides an unrepentantly catchy single sandwiched between layers of useless chaff. Ten years later, its safe to say that I've given up. ''Clarity'' is perfect.\"<ref name=\"PNT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2009-03-05/music/jimmy-eat-world-a-decade-of-clarity/|title= Jimmy Eat World: A Decade of ''Clarity''|website=[[Phoenix New Times]]|author=Cottell, Pete|date=5 March 2009|accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> Leor Galil of the [[Bostonist]], noted that, \"The album has been hailed as a cult and indie classic, and is one of a few go-to records that cemented an aural aesthetic known as emo, and is a genuinely deft and moving piece of music from start to finish. No wonder a proposal for [[Continuum International Publishing Group|Continuum]]'s [[33\u2153|33\u2153 book series]] about ''Clarity'' is in the running for potential-future publication.\"<ref name=\"TB\">{{cite web|url=http://bostonist.com/2009/02/26/preview_jimmy_eat_worlds_clarity_x.php|title=Preview: Jimmy Eat World's Clarity X 10 Tour|publisher=[[Bostonist]]|author=Galil, Leor|date=26 February 2009|accessdate=23 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323172438/http://bostonist.com/2009/02/26/preview_jimmy_eat_worlds_clarity_x.php|archivedate=23 March 2012}}</ref> Writing in 2003, [[Andy Greenwald]] called it \"one of the most fiercely beloved rock 'n' roll records of the last decade. It is name-checked by every single contemporary emo band as their favorite album, as a mind-bending milemarker that proved that punk rock could be tuneful, emotional, wide-ranging, and ambitious.\"<ref name=\"Greenwald, 103-104\"/> William Goodman of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' described it as a \"benchmark emo and pop-punk classic.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2008/11/jimmy-eat-world-announce-10th-anniversary-tour/|title=Jimmy Eat World Announce 10th Anniversary Tour|work=Spin|accessdate=May 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nUpon its re-issue in 2007, ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' magazine awarded a 4.5 star rating and noted that it was, \"1999's masterful ''Clarity'' that established a foundation for 21st century emo. Dozens of weepy bottom-feeders have tried to write mid-20s angst anthems better than the soaring \"Lucky Denver Mint\" or the delicately heartbroken \"Just Watch The Fireworks\"\u2013 but few have succeeded.\"<ref name=\"Blender\"/> [[AllMusic]]'s Mark Vanderhoff stated \"''Clarity'' mixes introspective balladry with power-chord punk rock, elements of chamber pop, and subtle doses of electronica to create a remarkably unique album\".<ref name=\"AMG\"/> Tim Nelson of the [[BBC]] was praiseworthy in his 2007 review of the remastering. \"The band and Trombino deserve credit for blending heartfelt, yearning vocals and rock dynamics with adventurous production and unique instrumentation\"<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/8xzf/ |title=Jimmy Eat World, Clarity|publisher=[[BBC]]|author=Nelson, Tim|date=7 August 2007|accessdate=13 August 2007|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20071021085323/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/8xzf/|archivedate=October 21, 2007}}</ref> ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' included the album in their \"10 Classic Albums of 1999\" feature. Scott Heisel wrote, \"Like Weezer's ''Pinkerton'' before it, the album has gone on to serve as the birthplace of emo's third wave. The sixteen-minute closing track \"Goodbye Sky Harbor\", with its organic breakdown/electronic build up is often imitated but never duplicated. Proving its far better to test your own limits than rely on the parameters of others \u2013 which is the exact reason why ''Clarity'' resonates with tens of thousands of people, a decade later\".<ref name=\"AltPress2\">{{Citation | title = 10 Classic Albums of '99 \u2013 Jimmy Eat World : ''Clarity'' | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/42277775@N03/3942770896/sizes/o/ | newspaper = [[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] | date = September 1999|author=Drake, Paul|issue=254|page=71|accessdate=2009-11-11|issn = 1065-1667}}</ref> Nate Chinen, writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', accounted that \"''Clarity'' was a pivotal album for Jimmy Eat World, the first to feature Jim Adkins on lead vocals instead of Mr. Linton and the last to reflect the heart-on-sleeve values of emocore more than the hard gleam of pop-punk. The songs convey acute self-awareness along with flashes of grace and insolence: the album is a pitch-perfect teenage plaint.\"<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/25/arts/music/25term.html|title= Years Later, an Appeal to Heart and Head|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Chinen, Nate|date=24 February 2009|accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref> ''[[Kerrang!]]'' magazine awarded the album five K's, which indicates \"classic\", and also labelled the album as the band's \"Essential Purchase\" in an article years later, stating: \"Glorious is perhaps the best word to capture the essence of ''Clarity''. Overflowing with flawless melodies backed up not only by magnificent musicianship but a ton of heart, this is the album that renders the label 'emo' redundant. Every note and syllable resonates with the kind of heartfelt emotion we'd like to think is poured into everything we listen to\".<ref name=\"Kerr\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.kerrang.com/wheretostartwith/artists/jimmy_eat_world |title=Where to Start: Jimmy Eat World |magazine=[[Kerrang!]] |accessdate=2009-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403071942/http://www.kerrang.com/wheretostartwith/artists/jimmy_eat_world |archivedate=2010-04-03 }}</ref>\n\nHarry Guerin of [[RT\u00c9 Entertainment]] gave the album a full five star rating in his review. He described the album as a, \"dense, beautiful collection which sees them bring in orchestras, drum loops and programming and find space for killer choruses, ballads and left field forays. The shortest song is under three minutes, the longest over 16 and the more you listen to all of them the more you'll wonder why this masterpiece wasn't massive\"<ref name=\"RTE\"/> ''[[Record Collector]]'' was also highly favourable. Eleanor Goodman awarded four out of five stars in her review and commented, \"though the multicoloured cover of 1999\u2019s ''Clarity'' became familiar in music shops, its combination of melancholy, introspective pop with faster punk rock broke the band in the US\".<ref name=\"RC\"/> [[Sputnikmusic]] staff reviewer Andrew Hartwig rated the album with a \"Superb\" 4.5 out of 5 rating. He praised the musicianship of the band and stated that \"Musically, the band are excellent. The drumming is sophisticated and original and the use of two guitars is a great addition to the band. The aforementioned range of added instruments adds immensely to the arrangements of the songs\". He went on to summarize, \"''Clarity'' is an album full of sensible pop songs, replay value and a diverse range of instruments and sounds. Truly one of the best albums of the 90s\".<ref name=\"Sputnik\"/> Charles Merwin of ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' gave the album an \"A\" grade and called it a \"minor masterpiece \u2014 a product of its time and as important to modern emo as [[Weezer]]'s \"''[[Pinkerton (album)|Pinkerton]]''\".<ref name=\"Stylus\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll lyrics written by Jim Adkins and Tom Linton; music composed by [[Jimmy Eat World]].<ref name=\"Credits\">{{cite AV media notes|title = Clarity|others = Jimmy Eat World|year = 1999|type = CD|publisher = Capitol Records}}</ref>\n{{tracklist|\n|title1= Table for Glasses\n|length1 = 4:22\n|title2 = Lucky Denver Mint\n|length2= 3:50\n|title3 = Your New Aesthetic\n|length3 = 2:50\n|title4 = Believe in What You Want\n|length4 = 3:08\n|title5 = A Sunday\n|length5= 4:33\n|title6 = Crush\n|length6 = 3:11\n|title7 = 12.23.95\n|length7 = 3:45\n|title8 = Ten\n|length8 = 3:49\n|title9 = Just Watch the Fireworks\n|length9 = 7:03\n|title10 = For Me This Is Heaven\n|length10 = 4:04\n|title11 = Blister\n|length11 = 3:30\n|title12= Clarity\n|length12 = 4:04\n|title13 = Goodbye Sky Harbor\n|length13 = 16:13\n}}\n\n;Bonus tracks\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = 2007 reissue bonus tracks\n| title14 = Christmas Card\n| length14 = 2:48\n| title15 = [[Sweetness (Jimmy Eat World song)|Sweetness]]\n| length15 = 3:39\n| note15 = studio [[Demo (music)|demo]]\n}}\n\n==Other Mixes==\n\n[[Chris Lord-Alge]] remixed both \"Lucky Denver Mint\" and \"Blister\". His mix of \"Lucky Denver Mint\" appeared on the \"Lucky Denver Mint\" promotional CD and the soundtrack to the film [[Never Been Kissed]]. His mix of \"Blister\" appeared on the \"Blister\" CD maxi single.\n\n==Appearance in other media==\n\nThe line \"It's to Jimmy Eat World and those nights in my car when the 'first star you see may not be a star.' I'm not your star -- isn't that what you said what you thought the song meant?\" from [[Something Corporate]]'s 2003 song \"[[Konstantine (song)|Konstantine]]\" is a direct reference to lyrics from the song \"For Me This is Heaven.\"\n\nOn [[The Wonder Years (band)|The Wonder Years]] track \"Solo & Chewy: Holdin' It Down\" off of their 2008 EP titled ''Won't Be Pathetic Forever'', they make reference to both the album ''Clarity'' and specifically the song \"Goodbye Sky Harbor\" with the line \"Arizona's airport is called Sky Harbor. I wonder if that's what the last song on ''Clarity''<nowiki/>'s about?\"\n\nBritish band [[Moose Blood]] reference the album, including an allusion to the song \"A Sunday\" in their song \"Bukowski\", with the lyrics \"I'll introduce you to ''Clarity'', teach you the words to [[The Sound of Settling]], and make you watch [[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]] on a Sunday, maybe one day.\"\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title=Clarity ''liner notes''|year=1999|publisher=[[Capitol Records]]}}</ref>\n\n;Jimmy Eat World\n* Jim Adkins&nbsp;\u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[guitars]], [[piano]], [[Keyboard instrument|keys]], [[String instrument|string]] [[arrangement]], [[lyrics]], [[art direction]], backing vocals on \"Blister\"\n* Rick Burch&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]]\n* Zach Lind&nbsp;\u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]], [[Vibraphone|vibes]], [[Bell (instrument)|bells]], [[chimes]], [[Programming (music)|programming]]\n* Tom Linton&nbsp;\u2013 [[guitars]], backing vocals, lyrics, lead vocals on \"Blister\"\n\n;Additional musicians\n* Joel Derouin&nbsp;\u2013 [[violin]]\n* Suzie Katayama&nbsp;\u2013 [[cello]], string arrangement\n* [[Mark Trombino]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[minimoog]], [[Music sequencer|sequencing]], additional percussion, programming\n\n;Production\n* Dean Fisher&nbsp;\u2013 [[Audio engineering|engineering assistant]]\n* Brian Gardner&nbsp;\u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n* [[Nick Raskulinecz]]&nbsp;\u2013 engineering assistant\n* Ron Rivera&nbsp;\u2013 engineering assistant\n* Justin Smith&nbsp;\u2013 engineering assistant\n* [[Mark Trombino]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Record producer|production]], engineering, [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n\n==References==\n; Footnotes\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n; Citations\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|editor1-last=McMahon|editor1-first=James|title=Rock's Biggest Secrets Revealed!|journal=Kerrang!|date=8 August 2015|issue=1580|publisher=Bauer Media Group|location=London|issn=0262-6624}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sharpe-Young |first=Garry |title=New Wave of American Heavy Metal |year=2005 |publisher=Zonda Books |location=New Plymouth, N.Z. |isbn=9780958268400 |edition=1st}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the album, which is allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n* [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLmrRAbUdPIYGu-HbxSeWBZn1o1aO08m_p ''Clarity''] (expanded version) at [[YouTube]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n\n{{Jimmy Eat World}}\n\n[[Category:1999 albums]]\n[[Category:Jimmy Eat World albums]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Mark Trombino]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Sound City Studios]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Clarity\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jimmy Eat World]]\n| cover      = Clarity.jpeg\n| alt        = A 2x2 image of 4 different photographs, including inside a body, red fingerprints, light, and the ocean. The words \"JIMMY EAT WORLD.CLARITY\" can be seen along with the image. The big word \"CLARITY.\" can be seen on the left of the image.\n| released   = {{start date|1999|02|23}}\n| recorded   = 1998\u20131999\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Sound City and Clear Lake Audio ([[Los Angeles]])\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[emo]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[indie rock]]\n* [[punk rock]]\n}}<!--All the genres are cited within the \"Reception and legacy\" section-->\n| length     = 64:22\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| producer   = [[Mark Trombino]]\n| prev_title = [[Static Prevails]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Singles (Jimmy Eat World album)|Singles]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Clarity\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Lucky Denver Mint\n | single1date = January 1, 1999\n | single2     = Blister\n | single2date = July 19, 1999\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Clarity''''' (stylized as '''''.CLARITY''''' and '''''CLARITY.''''') is the third studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Jimmy Eat World]], released on February 23, 1999, by [[Capitol Records]]. Overlooked upon its release, ''Clarity'' has since amassed [[cult status]] and critical acclaim, and has been lauded as one of the best [[emo music|emo records]] of all time.<ref name=\"RS1\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/40-greatest-emo-albums-of-all-time-20160301/jimmy-eat-world-clarity-1999-20160225 |title= 40 Greatest Emo Albums of All Time, #13|magazine=[[Rolling Stone Magazine]]|author=Bayer, Jonah|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"PNT2\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com/uponsun/2009/03/jimmy_eat_worlds_clarity_anniv.php |title= Jimmy Eat World's Clarity Anniversary Show Impressive|website=[[The Phoenix New Times]]|author=Cizmar, Martin|date=8 March 2009|accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref> Praise centered on its dynamic [[instrumentation]], as well as the heartfelt delivery of singer-guitarist-lyricist [[Jim Adkins]]. Various music critics have credited the album for serving as a huge influence on later emo music.<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com/uponsun/2008/11/jimmy_eat_world_celebrates_ann.php |title=Jimmy Eat World Celebrates Anniversary of Clarity By Playing It Live|author=Cizmar, Martin|website=[[The Phoenix New Times]]|date=10 November 2008|accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Spin1\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/jimmy-eat-world-celebrate-10-years-clarity?page=0%2C1 |title=Jimmy Eat World Celebrate 10 Years of 'Clarity'|author=Gaston, Peter|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=24 February 2009|accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"HWI\">{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodiconmagazine.com/2009/03/10/jimmy-eat-world-celebrate-a-decade-of-%E2%80%9Cclarity%E2%80%9D-in-la/|title=Jimmy Eat World Celebrate a Decade of \"Clarity\" in LA|publisher=Hollywood Icon|date=10 March 2009|accessdate=22 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817234348/http://hollywoodiconmagazine.com/2009/03/10/jimmy-eat-world-celebrate-a-decade-of-%E2%80%9Cclarity%E2%80%9D-in-la/|archivedate=17 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\nDuring breaks in touring in support of ''Static Prevails'', Adkins worked at an art store. While working at this store, \"Table for Glasses\" came about.<ref name=trackbytrack>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmyeatworld.com/clarity/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716202344/http://www.jimmyeatworld.com/clarity/|title=CLARITY TRACK BY TRACK|archivedate=16 July 2009|work=jimmyeatworld.com|accessdate=17 May 2015}}</ref> Adkins learned about shows that featured art pieces from local artists.<ref name=trackbytrack/> Adkins was waiting for a friend's piece to begin when he spotted a girl clearing the area with the end of her dress.<ref name=trackbytrack/> The girl walked towards \"a candle lit table that had already been set up. She just sat there picking out the dirt from her dress\", recalls Adkins.<ref name=trackbytrack/> \"Table for Glasses\" was one of a few songs that was intended for \"a side project of quiet songs\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> The project never got beyond jamming, and thus the songs were considered for ''Clarity''.<ref name=trackbytrack/> \"Lucky Denver Mint\" was inspired by a night out in Las Vegas Adkins had with a friend.<ref name=McMahon19>McMahon, ed. 2015, p. 19</ref> Adkins was too young to consume alcohol and instead gambled, eventually spending all of his money.<ref name=McMahon19/> As a result, Adkins spent the remainder of the night \"walking around feeling lost.\"<ref name=McMahon19/>\n\n\"Your New Aesthetic\" was originally a \"very mellow\" song, but was turned into \"a more aggressive, dark rock song\", as Lind notes.<ref name=trackbytrack/> This version was named \"Skeleton\" as the guitar sections between the verses \"reminded us of horror film music\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> It featured different lyrics but Adkins thought he could improve upon them and changed the lyrics from the mellow version.<ref name=trackbytrack/>\n\nThe lyrics for \"Goodbye Sky Harbor\" were based on the John Irving novel ''[[A Prayer for Owen Meany]]''.<ref name=COS>{{cite web|author=Ben Kaye |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/06/dissected-jimmy-eat-world-with-jim-adkins/4/|title=Dissected: Jimmy Eat World (with Jim Adkins)|work=Consequence of Sound|page=4|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Recording==\n{{quote box|quote= The atmosphere of the Clarity sessions was very encouraging for experimentation. Any idea was explored for some element to make the song better. I would think a song was totally finished and then one of the guys in the band or [producer] Mark [Trombino] would bring up an idea that really closed the deal.<ref name=trackbytrack/>|source= \u2013 Jim Adkins, on the recording sessions for ''Clarity'', 2009|width=25%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}\nOn recording \"Table for Glasses\", Adkins said the band learned \"if you aren't doing a lot, it doesn't take a lot to get a big dynamic impact\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> Adkins noted the cello was \"a good example of that\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> Susie Katayama provided Adkins assistance in writing and arranging the string parts for some of the songs.<ref name=trackbytrack/> The band recorded two different drum sets on \"Lucky Denver Mint\", a first for the band.<ref name=trackbytrack/> They had liked the effect, and as a result, used two sets on \"Ten\" and \"Goodbye Sky Harbor\".<ref name=trackbytrack/> The album was recorded in late 1998 to early 1999 at Sound City and Clear Lake Audio, both in [[North Hollywood]], with the tracks' mixing occurring at One on One in [[Los Angeles]] and Bernie Grundman Mastering in Hollywood.<ref name=\"AltPress2\"/>\n\n''Clarity'' marks the start of Jim Adkins - as opposed to Tom Linton - providing lead vocals. With the exception of the song \"Blister\" and \"Your New Aesthetic,\" Tom from this point on only provided backing vocals on various tracks until 2010's \"Action Needs an Audience\" off their album ''Invented''.<ref>{{cite web |author=Justin Gerber|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/06/dissected-jimmy-eat-world-with-jim-adkins/8/|title=Dissected: Jimmy Eat World (with Jim Adkins)|work=Consequence of Sound|page=8|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nAdkins revealed that despite the fact the album was \"complete\", it had no immediate release date.<ref name=trackbytrack/> The group's A&R guy suggested an EP with a few more songs.<ref name=trackbytrack/> [[Vinnie Fiorello]] of [[Less Than Jake]], who ran the label [[Fueled by Ramen]], was contacted and supported the idea.<ref name=trackbytrack/> The ''Jimmy Eat World'' EP was released by Fueled by Ramen<ref name=NWAHM182>Sharpe-Young 2005, p. 182</ref> on December 14, 1998<ref name=JEWEP>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmyeatworld.com/discography/detail.aspx?pid=393|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806222522/http://www.jimmyeatworld.com/discography/detail.aspx?pid=393|title=Jimmy Eat World|archivedate=6 August 2012|work=jimmyeatworld.com|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> and featured two songs from ''Clarity'': \"Lucky Denver Mint\" and \"For Me This Is Heaven\".{{#tag:ref|U.S. Fueled by Ramen FBR020<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fueledbyramen.com/releases/index.php?id=020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030808154417/http://www.fueledbyramen.com/releases/index.php?id=020|title=Fueled By Ramen - Releases|archivedate=8 August 2003|work=fueledbyramen.com|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} Los Angeles-based radio station KROQ picked up on \"Lucky Denver Mint\",<ref name=NWAHM182/> which resulted in a big interest in the song that gained it a place in the [[Drew Barrymore]] film ''[[Never Been Kissed]]''.<ref name=NWAHM182/> After this, the band was given a release date for the album.<ref name=trackbytrack/> Adkins had a \"strong suspicion\" that the production staff was purposely \"keeping from us that the label had no intention of releasing ''Clarity''\", prior to the airplay from KROQ.<ref name=trackbytrack/> Adkins said that major labels were good at selling large sums of albums but did not have the \"infrastructure to develop a band like us\".<ref name=trackbytrack/>\n\n''Clarity'' was released by [[Capitol Records]] on February 23, 1999.{{#tag:ref|U.S. Capitol CDP 7243 8 55950 2 8|group=\"nb\"}} However, despite critical praise and promotion of \"Lucky Denver Mint\" in the film ''[[Never Been Kissed]]'', ''Clarity'' was commercially unsuccessful in a musical climate dominated by [[teen pop]], and the band was dropped from Capitol Records the following year.<ref name=\"Greenwald, 103-104\">Greenwald, pp. 103\u2013104.</ref>\n\nAfter being dropped by Capitol, the band used this time to undertake extensive touring which allowed them to self-fund recording sessions for their eventual mainstream breakthrough, ''[[Bleed American]]'' (2001).<ref name=\"AP\"/> \n\nAlong with ''[[Static Prevails]]'' (1996), the album was re-released on May 15, 2007. The reissue included \"Christmas Card\" and a studio demo of \"Sweetness\" as bonus tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1516|title=AP Exclusive: Jimmy Eat World to reissue first two albums|work=Alternative Press|date=November 16, 2006|accessdate=August 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822204033/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1516|archive-date=August 22, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Two years later, the band released ''[[Clarity Live]]'' (2009), recorded during its commemorative tenth anniversary tour.\n\nThe 2009 vinyl re-release package included the two new bonus tracks as well as a ''Clarity 2009'' tour T-shirt. The 16 pictures used on the album's cover were shot by Paul Drake, Crissy Piper and J Gnewikow. For the 2009 re-issue, all 16 images appear on the front of the record. Art company The Uprising were hired to re-work the art for the 2009 release, using the original images, saying, \"...we were brought on to reconstruct and reinterpret the original artwork. We wanted to stay true to the original, but give it a slightly more sophisticated and updated look & feel. These reconstructions are always a little tricky because you rarely get all of the original art assets you need, but this turned out fantastic. And the actual prints look amazing!\".<ref>[http://www.theuprisingintl.com/blog/2009/01/22/jimmy-eat-world-10th-anniversary-limited-edition-clarity-vinyl-reissue/ Jimmy Eat World - 10th Anniversary Limited Edition Clarity Vinyl Reissue] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408205121/http://www.theuprisingintl.com/blog/2009/01/22/jimmy-eat-world-10th-anniversary-limited-edition-clarity-vinyl-reissue/ |date=2009-04-08 }} The Uprising, January 22, 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.chrissypiper.com/index.html chrissypiper] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228074159/http://www.chrissypiper.com/index.html |date=2009-02-28 }} Chrissy Piper, Clarity photographer, February 2009</ref>\n\n==Clarity x 10 Tour==\nThe 2009 U.S. ''Clarity x 10'' Tour, celebrating the 10th anniversary of ''Clarity'', was announced in November 2008 and went across 10 dates in 10 different states. The tour opened on February 23rd, 2009, at Terminal 5 in [[New York City|New York]], with shows on February 24th in [[Washington, D.C.]], February 25th in Trocadero Theater in [[Philadelphia]], February 26th at the [[House of Blues]] in [[Boston]], February 28th at the [[Metro Chicago|Metro]] in [[Chicago]], March 2nd at the Ogden Theater in [[Denver]], March 4th at The Fillmore in [[San Francisco]], March 5th at [[Club Nokia]] in [[Los Angeles]], and March 6th at [[San Diego]]'s House of Blues, before finally ending in the band's home state of Arizona on March 7th at the Marquee Theatre in [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]]. Support for the tour came from No Knife and Reuben's Accomplice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://intunemusiconline.com/2009/03/24/jimmy-eat-world-reubens-accomplice-nyc-223/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120605020520/http://intunemusiconline.com/2009/03/24/jimmy-eat-world-reubens-accomplice-nyc-223/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-06-05 |title=inTuneMusic Online: Jimmy Eat World Clarity Tour |accessdate=2009-03-24 |author=Ambrose, Anthony |date=2009-03-24 }}</ref> The band, who had been extensively rehearsing in-studio, performed a rehearsal live over the internet on February 12th, 2009. The band also been used the [[social network]] [[Twitter]] to update and share photos and other material from the studio.<ref name=\"NME4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/jimmy-eat-world/40965 |title= Jimmy Eat World announce 'Clarity' tour. The 10 shows will see band play 1999 album in its entirety |work=[[NME]]|author=Staff|date=10 November 2008|accessdate=11 November 2008}}</ref> The band released ''[[Clarity Live]]'' - a digital-only release of the ''Clarity x 10'' tour's finale, recorded in Tempe - on April 7, 2009.<ref name=\"NME2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/jimmy-eat-world/43191 |title= Jimmy Eat World to release 'Clarity Live' |work=[[NME]]|author=Staff|date=4 March 2009|accessdate=5 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n{{Album ratings\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/clarity-mw0000602620 |title= ''Clarity'' \u2013 Jimmy Eat World|website=[[AllMusic]]|author=Vanderhoff, Mark|accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"AltPress\">{{Citation | title = Jimmy Eat World: ''Clarity'' (Capitol)| newspaper = [[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] | date = February 1999|author=Heisel, Scott|issue=124|page=45|issn = 1065-1667}}<!--|accessdate=11 September 2003--></ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Blender\">{{Citation | title = Jimmy Eat World: ''Clarity'' (Capitol)| newspaper = [[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] | date = July 2007|author=Greenwald, Andy|issn = 1534-0554|authorlink = Andy Greenwald|issue=60}}<!--|accessdate=11 July 2007--></ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev4Score = 5/5<ref name=\"Kerr Review\">{{Citation | title = Jimmy Eat World: ''Clarity'' (Capitol)| newspaper = [[Kerrang!]] | date = February 1999|author=Brannigan, Paul|issue=795|page=49}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev5Score = 3.5/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/18878-clarity|title=Jimmy Eat World: ''Clarity''|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=16 May 2010|last=DiCrescenzo|first=Brent|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603120738/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/18878-clarity|archivedate=3 June 2008}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Record Collector]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"RC\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.recordcollectormag.com/reviews/review-detail/1380 |title=Jimmy Eat World \u2013 ''Clarity''|journal=[[Record Collector]]|author=Goodman, Eleanor|issue=342|date=November 2007|accessdate=16 May 2010}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Jimmy Eat World|last=Ryan|first=Chris|title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|edition=4th|year=2004|isbn=0-7432-0169-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/432 432]|title-link=The Rolling Stone Album Guide}}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[RT\u00c9 Entertainment]]\n| rev8Score= {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"RTE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2002/0910/jimmyeatworldalbums.html |title=Jimmy Eat World \u2013 ''Clarity''|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Entertainment]]|author=Guerin, Harry |date=9 August 2007|accessdate=16 May 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107102327/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2002/0910/jimmyeatworldalbums.html|archivedate=7 November 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev9Score = 4.5/5<ref name=\"Sputnik\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sputnikmusic.com/album.php?albumid=453|title=Jimmy Eat World: Clarity|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|author=Hartwig, Andrew|date=17 September 2005|accessdate=13 November 2009}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Stylus Magazine]]''\n| rev10Score = A<ref name=\"Stylus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/jimmy-eat-world/clarity.htm |title=Jimmy Eat World \u2013 ''Clarity'' \u2013 Review |work=[[Stylus Magazine]] |author=Merwin, Charles |date=9 August 2007 |accessdate=16 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503053050/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/jimmy-eat-world/clarity.htm |archivedate=3 May 2010 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nDespite being largely overlooked upon its release, the album's critical stature has grown in time. A contemporaneous review of ''Clarity'' by ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' was dismissive of the album.<ref name=\"pitchfork\"/> In retrospect, the album is now viewed as a \"masterpiece\", a \"landmark album of the 1990s\", and \"the ''[[Led Zeppelin IV]]'' of emo rock\".<ref name=\"Spin1\"/><ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web|url=http://absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?p=37646582#post=37646582 |title= Jimmy Eat World \u2013 Clarity Live|website=[[AbsolutePunk]]|author=Tate, Jason|date=3 March 2009|accessdate=4 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"RTE\"/> In 2008, ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine polled members of seventeen modern-day bands, all of whom cited [[Jim Adkins]]\u2019 writing and performance on the record as a primary influence.<ref name=\"Hip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hiponline.com/6261/jimmy-eat-world-announce-clarity-tour.html|title=Jimmy Eat World announce Clarity tour|publisher=Hip Online|accessdate=10 November 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121231072207/http://www.hiponline.com/6261/jimmy-eat-world-announce-clarity-tour.html|archivedate=31 December 2012}}</ref> Similarly, [[Manchester Orchestra]] bassist Jonathan Corley, in an interview with ''[[Rip It Up (magazine)|Rip it Up]]'' magazine, said that ''Clarity'' was one of his all-time favourite records and one that \"changed the way I look at music.\"<ref name=\"RIU\">{{cite web|url=http://ripitup.co.nz/contentitem/interview-manchester-orchestra/852 |title=Interview \u2013 Manchester Orchestra |publisher=[[Rip It Up (magazine)|Rip it Up]] |date=9 September 2010 |accessdate=23 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129050513/http://ripitup.co.nz/contentitem/interview-manchester-orchestra/852 |archivedate=29 November 2010 }}</ref> Preceding the band's tenth anniversary tour of the album, Pete Cottell of the ''[[Phoenix New Times]]'' wrote, \"What's truly admirable about the album is that it moves in so many different directions without getting lost on its journey. There's a tirade against shameless conformity (\"Your New Aesthetic\"), a herky-jerky, post-punk Police homage (\"Believe in What You Want\"), and a shimmering power ballad (\"For Me This Is Heaven\"). While (\"Goodbye Sky Harbor\") spills over with layered harmonies, chiming guitar passages, and 808 spurt. Unlike the 12 other tracks on ''Clarity'', it's an almost impossible undertaking upon first listen. Once you've made it to the 13-minute mark, however, you'll never hit the skip button again.\" Cottell also stated \"I intently listened to each of the 13 tracks, fearing I would be let down by yet another alt-rock album that had little to offer besides an unrepentantly catchy single sandwiched between layers of useless chaff. Ten years later, its safe to say that I've given up. ''Clarity'' is perfect.\"<ref name=\"PNT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2009-03-05/music/jimmy-eat-world-a-decade-of-clarity/|title= Jimmy Eat World: A Decade of ''Clarity''|website=[[Phoenix New Times]]|author=Cottell, Pete|date=5 March 2009|accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> Leor Galil of the [[Bostonist]], noted that, \"The album has been hailed as a cult and indie classic, and is one of a few go-to records that cemented an aural aesthetic known as emo, and is a genuinely deft and moving piece of music from start to finish. No wonder a proposal for [[Continuum International Publishing Group|Continuum]]'s [[33\u2153|33\u2153 book series]] about ''Clarity'' is in the running for potential-future publication.\"<ref name=\"TB\">{{cite web|url=http://bostonist.com/2009/02/26/preview_jimmy_eat_worlds_clarity_x.php|title=Preview: Jimmy Eat World's Clarity X 10 Tour|publisher=[[Bostonist]]|author=Galil, Leor|date=26 February 2009|accessdate=23 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323172438/http://bostonist.com/2009/02/26/preview_jimmy_eat_worlds_clarity_x.php|archivedate=23 March 2012}}</ref> Writing in 2003, [[Andy Greenwald]] called it \"one of the most fiercely beloved rock 'n' roll records of the last decade. It is name-checked by every single contemporary emo band as their favorite album, as a mind-bending milemarker that proved that punk rock could be tuneful, emotional, wide-ranging, and ambitious.\"<ref name=\"Greenwald, 103-104\"/> William Goodman of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' described it as a \"benchmark emo and pop-punk classic.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2008/11/jimmy-eat-world-announce-10th-anniversary-tour/|title=Jimmy Eat World Announce 10th Anniversary Tour|work=Spin|accessdate=May 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nUpon its re-issue in 2007, ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' magazine awarded a 4.5 star rating and noted that it was, \"1999's masterful ''Clarity'' that established a foundation for 21st century emo. Dozens of weepy bottom-feeders have tried to write mid-20s angst anthems better than the soaring \"Lucky Denver Mint\" or the delicately heartbroken \"Just Watch The Fireworks\"\u2013 but few have succeeded.\"<ref name=\"Blender\"/> [[AllMusic]]'s Mark Vanderhoff stated \"''Clarity'' mixes introspective balladry with power-chord punk rock, elements of chamber pop, and subtle doses of electronica to create a remarkably unique album\".<ref name=\"AMG\"/> Tim Nelson of the [[BBC]] was praiseworthy in his 2007 review of the remastering. \"The band and Trombino deserve credit for blending heartfelt, yearning vocals and rock dynamics with adventurous production and unique instrumentation\"<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/8xzf/ |title=Jimmy Eat World, Clarity|publisher=[[BBC]]|author=Nelson, Tim|date=7 August 2007|accessdate=13 August 2007|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20071021085323/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/8xzf/|archivedate=October 21, 2007}}</ref> ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' included the album in their \"10 Classic Albums of 1999\" feature. Scott Heisel wrote, \"Like Weezer's ''Pinkerton'' before it, the album has gone on to serve as the birthplace of emo's third wave. The sixteen-minute closing track \"Goodbye Sky Harbor\", with its organic breakdown/electronic build up is often imitated but never duplicated. Proving its far better to test your own limits than rely on the parameters of others \u2013 which is the exact reason why ''Clarity'' resonates with tens of thousands of people, a decade later\".<ref name=\"AltPress2\">{{Citation | title = 10 Classic Albums of '99 \u2013 Jimmy Eat World : ''Clarity'' | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/42277775@N03/3942770896/sizes/o/ | newspaper = [[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] | date = September 1999|author=Drake, Paul|issue=254|page=71|accessdate=2009-11-11|issn = 1065-1667}}</ref> Nate Chinen, writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', accounted that \"''Clarity'' was a pivotal album for Jimmy Eat World, the first to feature Jim Adkins on lead vocals instead of Mr. Linton and the last to reflect the heart-on-sleeve values of emocore more than the hard gleam of pop-punk. The songs convey acute self-awareness along with flashes of grace and insolence: the album is a pitch-perfect teenage plaint.\"<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/25/arts/music/25term.html|title= Years Later, an Appeal to Heart and Head|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Chinen, Nate|date=24 February 2009|accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref> ''[[Kerrang!]]'' magazine awarded the album five K's, which indicates \"classic\", and also labelled the album as the band's \"Essential Purchase\" in an article years later, stating: \"Glorious is perhaps the best word to capture the essence of ''Clarity''. Overflowing with flawless melodies backed up not only by magnificent musicianship but a ton of heart, this is the album that renders the label 'emo' redundant. Every note and syllable resonates with the kind of heartfelt emotion we'd like to think is poured into everything we listen to\".<ref name=\"Kerr\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.kerrang.com/wheretostartwith/artists/jimmy_eat_world |title=Where to Start: Jimmy Eat World |magazine=[[Kerrang!]] |accessdate=2009-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403071942/http://www.kerrang.com/wheretostartwith/artists/jimmy_eat_world |archivedate=2010-04-03 }}</ref>\n\nHarry Guerin of [[RT\u00c9 Entertainment]] gave the album a full five star rating in his review. He described the album as a, \"dense, beautiful collection which sees them bring in orchestras, drum loops and programming and find space for killer choruses, ballads and left field forays. The shortest song is under three minutes, the longest over 16 and the more you listen to all of them the more you'll wonder why this masterpiece wasn't massive\"<ref name=\"RTE\"/> ''[[Record Collector]]'' was also highly favourable. Eleanor Goodman awarded four out of five stars in her review and commented, \"though the multicoloured cover of 1999\u2019s ''Clarity'' became familiar in music shops, it's combination of melancholy, introspective pop with faster punk rock broke the band in the US\".<ref name=\"RC\"/> [[Sputnikmusic]] staff reviewer Andrew Hartwig rated the album with a \"Superb\" 4.5 out of 5 rating. He praised the musicianship of the band and stated that \"Musically, the band are excellent. The drumming is sophisticated and original and the use of two guitars is a great addition to the band. The aforementioned range of added instruments adds immensely to the arrangements of the songs\". He went on to summarize, \"''Clarity'' is an album full of sensible pop songs, replay value and a diverse range of instruments and sounds. Truly one of the best albums of the 90s\".<ref name=\"Sputnik\"/> Charles Merwin of ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' gave the album an \"A\" grade and called it a \"minor masterpiece \u2014 a product of its time and as important to modern emo as [[Weezer]]'s \"''[[Pinkerton (album)|Pinkerton]]''\".<ref name=\"Stylus\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll lyrics written by Jim Adkins and Tom Linton; music composed by [[Jimmy Eat World]].<ref name=\"Credits\">{{cite AV media notes|title = Clarity|others = Jimmy Eat World|year = 1999|type = CD|publisher = Capitol Records}}</ref>\n{{tracklist|\n|title1= Table for Glasses\n|length1 = 4:22\n|title2 = Lucky Denver Mint\n|length2= 3:50\n|title3 = Your New Aesthetic\n|length3 = 2:50\n|title4 = Believe in What You Want\n|length4 = 3:08\n|title5 = A Sunday\n|length5= 4:33\n|title6 = Crush\n|length6 = 3:11\n|title7 = 12.23.95\n|length7 = 3:45\n|title8 = Ten\n|length8 = 3:49\n|title9 = Just Watch the Fireworks\n|length9 = 7:03\n|title10 = For Me This Is Heaven\n|length10 = 4:04\n|title11 = Blister\n|length11 = 3:30\n|title12= Clarity\n|length12 = 4:04\n|title13 = Goodbye Sky Harbor\n|length13 = 16:13\n}}\n\n;Bonus tracks\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = 2007 reissue bonus tracks\n| title14 = Christmas Card\n| length14 = 2:48\n| title15 = [[Sweetness (Jimmy Eat World song)|Sweetness]]\n| length15 = 3:39\n| note15 = studio [[Demo (music)|demo]]\n}}\n\n==Other Mixes==\n\n[[Chris Lord-Alge]] remixed both \"Lucky Denver Mint\" and \"Blister\". His mix of \"Lucky Denver Mint\" appeared on the \"Lucky Denver Mint\" promotional CD and the soundtrack to the film [[Never Been Kissed]]. His mix of \"Blister\" appeared on the \"Blister\" CD maxi single.\n\n==Appearance in other media==\n\nThe line \"It's to Jimmy Eat World and those nights in my car when the 'first star you see may not be a star.' I'm not your star -- isn't that what you said what you thought the song meant?\" from [[Something Corporate]]'s 2003 song \"[[Konstantine (song)|Konstantine]]\" is a direct reference to lyrics from the song \"For Me This is Heaven.\"\n\nOn [[The Wonder Years (band)|The Wonder Years]] track \"Solo & Chewy: Holdin' It Down\" off of their 2008 EP titled ''Won't Be Pathetic Forever'', they make reference to both the album ''Clarity'' and specifically the song \"Goodbye Sky Harbor\" with the line \"Arizona's airport is called Sky Harbor. I wonder if that's what the last song on ''Clarity''<nowiki/>'s about?\"\n\nBritish band [[Moose Blood]] reference the album, including an allusion to the song \"A Sunday\" in their song \"Bukowski\", with the lyrics \"I'll introduce you to ''Clarity'', teach you the words to [[The Sound of Settling]], and make you watch [[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]] on a Sunday, maybe one day.\"\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title=Clarity ''liner notes''|year=1999|publisher=[[Capitol Records]]}}</ref>\n\n;Jimmy Eat World\n* Jim Adkins&nbsp;\u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[guitars]], [[piano]], [[Keyboard instrument|keys]], [[String instrument|string]] [[arrangement]], [[lyrics]], [[art direction]], backing vocals on \"Blister\"\n* Rick Burch&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]]\n* Zach Lind&nbsp;\u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]], [[Vibraphone|vibes]], [[Bell (instrument)|bells]], [[chimes]], [[Programming (music)|programming]]\n* Tom Linton&nbsp;\u2013 [[guitars]], backing vocals, lyrics, lead vocals on \"Blister\"\n\n;Additional musicians\n* Joel Derouin&nbsp;\u2013 [[violin]]\n* Suzie Katayama&nbsp;\u2013 [[cello]], string arrangement\n* [[Mark Trombino]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[minimoog]], [[Music sequencer|sequencing]], additional percussion, programming\n\n;Production\n* Dean Fisher&nbsp;\u2013 [[Audio engineering|engineering assistant]]\n* Brian Gardner&nbsp;\u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n* [[Nick Raskulinecz]]&nbsp;\u2013 engineering assistant\n* Ron Rivera&nbsp;\u2013 engineering assistant\n* Justin Smith&nbsp;\u2013 engineering assistant\n* [[Mark Trombino]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Record producer|production]], engineering, [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n\n==References==\n; Footnotes\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n; Citations\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|editor1-last=McMahon|editor1-first=James|title=Rock's Biggest Secrets Revealed!|journal=Kerrang!|date=8 August 2015|issue=1580|publisher=Bauer Media Group|location=London|issn=0262-6624}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sharpe-Young |first=Garry |title=New Wave of American Heavy Metal |year=2005 |publisher=Zonda Books 