{"title_page": "V. V. Giri", "text_new": "{{short description|Fourth President of India}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| name = Varahagiri Venkata Giri\n| image = VV Giri 1974 stamp of India.jpg| caption = V. V. Giri \n| office = [[List of Presidents of India|4th]] [[President of India]]\n| vicepresident = [[Gopal Swarup Pathak]]\n| term_start = 24 August 1969\n| term_end = 24 August 1974\n| predecessor = [[Mohammad Hidayatullah]] <small>(Acting)</small>\n| successor = [[Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Indira Gandhi]]\n| term_start2 = 3 May 1969\n| term_end2 = 20 July 1969\n| predecessor2 = [[Zakir Hussain (politician)|Zakir Hussain]]\n| successor2 = [[Mohammad Hidayatullah]] <small>(Acting)</small>\n| primeminister3 = [[Indira Gandhi]]\n| office3 = [[List of Vice Presidents of India|3rd]] [[Vice President of India]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Indira Gandhi]]\n| president3 = [[Zakir Hussain (politician)|Zakir Hussain]]\n| term_start3 = 13 May 1967\n| term_end3 = 3 May 1969\n| predecessor3 = [[Zakir Hussain (politician)|Zakir Hussain]]\n| successor3 = [[Gopal Swarup Pathak]]\n| office4 = [[List of Governors of Karnataka|Governor of Karnataka]]\n| 1blankname4 = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata4 = [[S. Nijalingappa]]\n| term_start4 = 2 April 1965\n| term_end4 = 13 May 1967\n| predecessor4 = [[Satyawant Mallannah Shrinagesh]]\n| successor4 = [[Gopal Swarup Pathak]]\n| office5 = [[List of Governors of Kerala|Governor of Kerala]]\n| 1blankname5 = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata5 = [[Pattom A. Thanu Pillai|Pattom Thanu Pillai]]<br/>[[R. Sankar]]\n| term_start5 = 1 July 1960\n| term_end5 = 2 April 1965\n| predecessor5 = [[Burgula Ramakrishna Rao]]\n| successor5 = [[Ajit Prasad Jain]]\n| office6 = [[List of Governors of Uttar Pradesh|Governor of Uttar Pradesh]]\n| 1blankname6 = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata6 = [[Sampurnanand]]\n| term_start6 = 10 June 1956\n| term_end6 = 30 June 1960\n| predecessor6 = [[Kanhaiyalal Maneklal Munshi]]\n| successor6 = [[Burgula Ramakrishna Rao]]\n| office7 = [[Minister of Industry|Minister of Labour and Industry]] for [[Madras Presidency]]\n| 1blankname7 = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata7 = [[Tanguturi Prakasam]]\n| term_start7 = 30 April 1946\n| term_end7 = 23 March 1947\n| birth_name = Varahagiri Venkata Giri\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1894|8|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Berhampur]] in [[Odisha]], [[India]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1980|6|24|1894|8|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Madras]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]<br />(now [[Chennai]])\n| party = [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n| spouse = Saraswati Bai (1904\u20131978)\n| relatives =\n*[[Adruti Laxmibai]] (sister)<ref name=\"Participation of Women of Ganjam District in the Freedom Movement of India\">{{cite web |author1=Dasarathi Bhuyan |title=Participation of Women of Ganjam District in the Freedom Movement of India |url=http://magazines.odisha.gov.in/Orissareview/2010/August/engpdf/august%202010.pdf |publisher=Orissa Review |accessdate=27 November 2018 |pages=18\u201320 }}</ref>\n*[[Palagummi Sainath]] (grandson)<ref name=\"cockburn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/cockburn08042005.html |title=Why Indian Farmers Kill Themselves; Why Lange's Photographs are Phony |publisher=Counterpunch.org |date=4 August 2005 |accessdate=29 November 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050807232632/http://www.counterpunch.org/cockburn08042005.html |archivedate=7 August 2005 }}</ref>\n| alma_mater = [[Khallikote College]]<br/>[[University College Dublin]]\n| awards = [[Bharat Ratna]] (1975)\n| signature = Varahagiri Venkatagiri Signature.jpg\n| signature_alt = Varahagiri Venkatagiri Signature in English\n}}\n\n'''Varahagiri Venkata Giri''' {{audio|Vvg.ogg|pronunciation}} (10 August 1894 \u2013 24 June 1980), commonly known as '''V. V. Giri''', was the [[List of Presidents of India|fourth]] [[president of India]] from 24 August 1969 to 24 August 1974.\n\nAs president, Giri was the only person to be elected as an independent candidate.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/bjp-vs-opposition-india-set-to-witness-tightest-presidential-poll-since-1969/story-sZ5LlpWvMBaxPULLoQHZbN.html |title=NDA vs Oppn: India might to witness tightest presidential poll since 1969 |author=Saubhadra Chatterji |date=26 April 2017 |website=[[Hindustan Times]]|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> He was succeeded by [[Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed]] as president in 1974.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/gal.html | title=Gallery of Indian Presidents |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212121818/http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/gal.html |archive-date=12 December 2017 |website=[[Press Information Bureau]] |publisher=Government of India |access-date=21 June 2018 }}</ref> After the end of his full term, Giri was honoured by the [[Government of India]] with the [[Bharat Ratna]] in 1975. Giri died on 24 June 1980. His great grandson V. Giri Shankar is an Advocate of the Madras High Court, Chennai.\n\n==Early life==\nGiri was born in [[Berhampur]], [[Odisha]] to a [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-speaking <ref>https://books.google.co.in/books?id=r2C2InxI0xAC&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72&dq=vv+giri+brahmin&source=bl&ots=o-BA_JrGWG&sig=ACfU3U0mJkPCBkYHTjuv5etqprwj8b7U9Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjIkM6E9q3mAhUWyzgGHeU6B9A4ChDoATACegQIBxAB</ref> family. His father, V. V. Jogayya  Pantulu, was a successful lawyer and political activist of the Indian National Congress.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Great Indian Patriots, Volume 1|author=P. Rajeswar Rao|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1991|isbn=9788170992806|location=India|pages=279\u2013282}}</ref> Giri's mother Subhadramma was active in the national movement in Berhampur during the [[Non Cooperation Movement|Non Cooperation]] and [[Civil Disobedience Movement]]s and was arrested for leading a strike for [[prohibition]] during the Civil Disobedience Movement.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Bina Kumari Sarma|title=Women's Role in the Freedom Movement in South Orissa|journal=Orissa Review|date=August 2010|pages=34\u201335|url=http://orissa.gov.in/e-magazine/Orissareview/2010/August/engpdf/34-38.pdf|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nGiri was married to Saraswati Bai and the couple had 14 children.<ref name=\"Rao1991\">{{cite book|author=P. Rajeswar Rao|title=The Great Indian Patriots|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eTrs9MF9374C&pg=PA278|year=1991|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-7099-280-6|page=282}}</ref>\n\nGiri completed his initial education at the [[Khallikote College]], then affiliated with [[Utkal University]], in Berhampur.<ref>{{cite web|title=Varahagiri Venkata Giri|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/234218/Varahagiri-Venkata-Giri|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> In 1913 he went to Ireland to study law which he did at [[University College Dublin]] and the [[King's Inns|Honourable Society of King's Inns, Dublin]] between 1913\u20131916.<ref>{{cite news|title=University College Dublin announces special scholarships for Indian students|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/university-college-dublin-announces-special-scholarships-for-indian-students/1/328125.html|accessdate=8 January 2015|publisher=India Today|date=6 November 2013}}</ref> Giri was one among the first crop of thirteen Indian students who sat the obligatory year long course at UCD in 1914\u201315. This was a requirement for being called to the Irish Bar through study at the King's Inns. In total, 50 Indian students studied at UCD between 1914 and 1917.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Irish Days, Indian Memories: V. V. Giri and Indian Law Students at University College Dublin, 1913\u20131916|author= Conor Mulvagh|publisher=Irish Academic Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-911024-18-7|location=Sallins|pages=43}}</ref>\n\nGiri and a fellow law student also enrolled to study on the full bachelor of arts course in UCD. Giri studied English, where he was lectured by [[Thomas MacDonagh]], and Political Economy. His lecturer in political economy was the reformer and co-operativist [[Thomas A. Finlay|Thomas A. Finlay SJ]].\n\nDuring the First World War, Giri travelled from Dublin to London and met with [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Gandhi wanted for Giri to join the Imperial war effort as a Red Cross Volunteer. Giri initially acceded to Gandhi's request but later regretted his decision. According to one of Giri's biographers, \"Gandhiji with his characteristic magnanimity relieved Giri of the obligation to join the Red Cross and did not breathe a word about it to anyone.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/gandhi-an-expelled-future-president-and-first-aid-crews-the-indians-of-1916-rising-1.2529440|title=Gandhi, an expelled future president and first aid crews: the Indians of 1916 Rising|author=Conor Mulvagh|date=10 February 2016|work=|newspaper=The Irish Times|access-date=17 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nGiri was active in both Indian and Irish politics during his studies. Along with fellow Indian students he produced a pamphlet documenting the abuse of Indians in South Africa. The pamphlet was intercepted by [[Indian Political Intelligence Office|Indian Political Intelligence]] and resulted in increased police scrutiny of Giri and his fellow students in Dublin.<ref name=\":0\" /> Meanwhile, anonymous articles were written by Indian students for the newspaper of the [[Irish Volunteers]] and in ''The National Student'', a UCD student magazine.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Irish Days, Indian Memories: V. V. Giri and Indian Law Students at University College Dublin, 1913\u20131916|author=Conor Mulvagh|publisher=Irish Academic Press|year=2016 |isbn=978-1-911024-18-7|location=Sallins, Co. Kildare, Ireland|pages=34, 49\u201350|quote=|via=http://irishacademicpress.ie/product/irish-days-indian-memories-v-v-giri-and-indian-law-students-at-university-college-dublin-1913-1916/}}</ref>\n\nHe was suspected of association with prominent ring leaders in the [[Easter Rising|1916 Rising]] including [[James Connolly]], [[Patrick Pearse|PH Pearse]] and the young [[\u00c9amon de Valera]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2005/08/04/why-indian-farmers-kill-themselves-why-lange-s-photographs-are-phony/|title=Why Indian Farmers Kill Themselves; Why Lange's Photographs are Phony|date=25 March 2005|publisher=Counter Punch |author=Alexander Cockburn |accessdate=19 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Bhattacharya2013\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iLxnAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA636|title=NOTHING BUT!|date=December 2013|publisher=Author Solutions|isbn=978-1-4828-1626-6|pages=636\u2013|author=Brigadier Samir Bhattacharya}}</ref><ref name=\"Lentz2014\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RwfKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1538|title=Heads of States and Governments Since 1945|date=4 February 2014|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-134-26497-1|pages=1538\u2013|author=Harris M. Lentz}}</ref> Giri was called to the Irish Bar on 21 June 1916 but he did not complete his studies for BA in UCD.<ref name=\":1\" /> Indian students were subjected to police raids following the 1916 Rising and Giri recounts how he was served with one month's notice to leave Ireland on 1 June 1916.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1916/jun/01/mr-t-a-chettiar-of-madras#S5CV0082P0_19160601_CWA_3|title=MR. T. A. CHETTIAR, OF MADRAS. (Hansard, 1 June 1916)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com|access-date=17 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nUpon returning to India in 1916 Giri enrolled at the [[Madras High Court]].<ref name=\"The Deccan Herald\">{{cite news|title=Worker's leader who turned President|url=http://archive.deccanherald.com/Deccanherald/aug082004/ac3.asp|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Deccan Herald|date=8 August 2004}}</ref> He also became a member of the Congress party, attended its [[Lucknow]] session and joined the [[Home Rule Movement]] of [[Annie Beasant]].<ref name=\"Jai2003 76\">{{cite book|author=Janak Raj Jai|title=Presidents of India, 1950\u20132003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r2C2InxI0xAC&pg=PA76|date=2003|publisher=Regency Publications|isbn=978-81-87498-65-0|page=76}}</ref> Giri abandoned a flourishing legal career in response to [[Mahatma Gandhi|Mahatma Gandhi's]] call for a [[Non-Cooperation Movement]] in 1920.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shekhawat need not compare himself to Giri: Shashi Bhushan|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/shekhawat-need-not-compare-himself-to-giri-shashi-bhushan/article1871463.ece|accessdate=8 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=12 July 2007}}</ref> In 1922, he was arrested for the first time for demonstrating against the sale of liquor shops.<ref name=\"The Deccan Herald\"/>\n\n=== Role in the labour movement ===\nGiri was closely associated with the labour and trade union movement in India throughout his career.<ref name=\"Reminiscences of Gandhiji\">{{cite book|author=Chandrashanker Shukla|title=Reminiscences of Gandhiji|date=March 1951|publisher=Vora & Co.|location=Bombay|page=108 |url=http://krishikosh.egranth.ac.in/bitstream/1/20434/1/G-2493.pdf|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref> Giri was a founding member of the [[All India Railwaymen's Federation]] which was formed in 1923 and served as its general secretary for over a decade.<ref>{{cite web|title=President of India speaking!|url=http://www.taxindiaonline.com/RC2/inside2.php3?filename=bnews_detail.php3&newsid=5743|publisher=taxindiaonline.com|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Chandrasekhar1985\">{{cite book|author=S. Chandrasekhar|title=Dimensions of Socio-political Change in Mysore, 1918\u201340 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zqz9SbueWk4C&pg=PA113|year=1985|publisher=Ashish Publishing House|isbn=978-0-8364-1471-4|pages=113\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"A principled politician\">{{cite news|title=A principled politician |url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/09/23/stories/2002092301370200.htm|accessdate=8 February 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=23 September 2002}}</ref> He was elected president of the [[All India Trade Union Congress]] for the first time in 1926.<ref name=\"Mansingh2006\">{{cite book|author=Surjit Mansingh|title=Historical Dictionary of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6HAeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA240|date=9 May 2006|publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=978-0-8108-6502-0|pages=240\u2013}}</ref> Giri also founded the Bengal Nagpur Railway Association and in 1928 led the workers of the [[Bengal Nagpur Railway]] in a non violent strike for the rights of [[Retrenchment|retrenched]] workers. The strike succeeded in forcing the [[British Raj|British Indian government]] and the management of the railway company to concede the workers' demands and is regarded as a milestone in the labour movement in India.<ref name=\"The Deccan Herald\"/><ref name=\"Reminiscences of Gandhiji\"/><ref name=\"A principled politician\"/>\nIn 1929, the Indian Trade Union Federation (ITUF) was formed by Giri, [[N. M. Joshi]] and others with Giri as the president. The split with the AITUC came about over the issue of cooperating with the Royal Commission on Labour. Giri and the ITUF leadership of liberals decided to cooperate with the Commission while the AITUC decided to boycott it.<ref name=\"Tarique\">{{cite book|author=Mohammad Tarique|title=Modern Indian History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pcKMD9XWyjAC&pg=SA7-PA2|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education|isbn=978-0-07-066030-4|pages=7\u2013}}</ref> The ITUF merged with the AITUC in 1939 and Giri became president of the AITUC for a second time in 1942.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sharit Bhowmik|title=The Labour Movement in India: Fractured Trade Unions and Vulnerable Workers|journal=Rethinking Development and Inequality|date=2013|volume=2|issue=Special Issue|page=86}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=AITUC \u2013 Our Leaders|url=http://aituc.in/leaders.html|publisher=AITUC|accessdate=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206153013/http://aituc.in/leaders.html|archive-date=6 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGiri was the Workers' Delegate of the Indian delegation at the [[International Labour Conference]] of the [[ILO]] in 1927.<ref>{{cite book|title=List of Indian Delegates and Advisers to International Labour Conferences (1919\u20132011)|publisher=V.V.Giri National Labour Institute, Ministry of Labour & Employment|location=NOIDA|url=http://www.vvgnli.org/sites/default/files/publication_files/List-of-Indian-Delegates-Advisors.pdf|accessdate=15 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207151828/http://www.vvgnli.org/sites/default/files/publication_files/List-of-Indian-Delegates-Advisors.pdf|archivedate=7 February 2015}}</ref> At the [[Round Table Conferences (India)|Second Round Table Conference]], Giri was present as a representative of the industrial workers of India.<ref name=\"Reminiscences of Gandhiji\"/> Giri worked towards getting the trade unions to support the freedom movement in India and was twice president of the AITUC which was closely allied with the Indian National Congress.<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\">{{cite book|author=Janak Raj Jai|title=Presidents of India, 1950\u20132003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r2C2InxI0xAC&pg=PA75|date=1 January 2003|publisher=Regency Publications|isbn=978-81-87498-65-0|pages=75\u2013}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral career in British India ==\nGiri was the best man in the politics when he was the president. Giri became a member of the [[Imperial Legislative Assembly]] in 1934.<ref>Narasingha P. Sil, ''Giri, Varahagiri Venkata (1894\u20131980), trade unionist and president of India'' in ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' (2004)</ref> He remained its member until 1937 and emerged a spokesman for matters of labour and trade unions in the Assembly.<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\"/>\n\nIn the General Elections of 1936, Giri defeated the Raja of Bobbili to become a member of the [[Madras Legislative Assembly]]. Between 1937\u20131939, he was Minister for Labour and Industry in the Congress government headed by [[C Rajagopalachari]].<ref name=\"Chaurasia2002\">{{cite book|author=Radhey Shyam Chaurasia|title=History of Modern India, 1707 A. D. to 2000 A. D|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MS_jrForJOoC&pg=PA300|date=1 January 2002 |publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|isbn=978-81-269-0085-5|pages=300\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Gandhi1997\">{{cite book|author=Rajmohan Gandhi|title=Rajaji: A Life|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JjPHeRd7_UYC&pg=PA171|year=1997|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-026967-3|pages=171\u2013}}</ref> Giri was appointed Governor of the National Planning Committee of the Indian National Congress in 1938. In 1939, the Congress ministries resigned in protest against the British decision to make India a party in the [[Second World War]]. Having returned to the labour movement, Giri was arrested and spent 15 months in prison till March 1941.<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\"/>\n\nFollowing the launch of the [[Quit India Movement]], Giri was imprisoned again by the colonial government in 1942.<ref name=\"GroverArora1994\">{{cite book|author1=Verinder Grover|author2=Ranjana Arora|title=Constitutional Schemes and Political Development in India: Towards Transfer of Power |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBCd9ZKzbUUC&pg=PA8|date=1 January 1994|publisher=Deep & Deep Publications|isbn=978-81-7100-539-0|pages=8\u2013}}</ref> He remained in prison when the AITUC met in [[Nagpur]] in 1943 where he was the president elect.<ref name=\"Singh1981\">{{cite book|author=Viv Bahadour Singh|title=Economic History of India: 1857\u20131956|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xeJEXFnGS6AC&pg=PA590|year=1981|publisher=Allied Publishers|pages=590\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Economic History of India: 1857\u20131956|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xeJEXFnGS6AC&pg=PA590|publisher=Allied Publishers|pages=590\u2013}}</ref> Giri served his sentence in the [[Vellore]] and [[Amravati|Amaravathi]] prisons.<ref name=\"Reddy2003\">{{cite book|author=A. Ranga Reddy|title=The State of Rayalaseema |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_g9T8UoCeO4C&pg=PA373|year=2003|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-7099-814-3|pages=373\u2013}}</ref> Giri remained in prison for three years, his longest sentence, until his release in 1945.<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\"/>\n\nIn the [[1946 Madras legislative assembly election|General Elections of 1946]], Giri was reelected to the Madras Legislative Assembly and became a minister again in charge of the labour portfolio under [[T. Prakasam]].<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\"/>\n\n== Career in independent India ==\nFrom 1947 to 1951, Giri served as India's first High Commissioner to [[Ceylon]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nirupama Rao presents credentials to Chandrika|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2004/09/18/stories/2004091807611300.htm|accessdate=8 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=18 September 2004}}</ref> In the [[General elections in India|General Elections of 1951]], he was elected to the [[1st Lok Sabha]] from [[Pathapatnam]] Lok Sabha Constituency in the [[Madras State]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Key Highlights of General Elections, 1951 to the First Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|location=New Delhi|page=15|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1951/VOL_1_51_LS.PDF|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Union Minister for Labour (1952\u20131954) ===\nOn being elected to Parliament, Giri was appointed Minister of Labour in 1952.<ref name=\"Hensman2013\">{{cite book|author=Rohini Hensman|title=Workers, Unions, and Global Capitalism: Lessons from India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ruusCMIQw7EC&pg=PT75|date=20 August 2013|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-51956-4|pages=75\u2013}}</ref> His policy initiatives as minister gave rise to the ''Giri Approach'' in industrial dispute resolution.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Labour Problems \u2014 The \"Giri Approach \"|journal=The Economic Weekly|date=13 September 1952|page=951|url=http://www.epw.in/system/files/pdf/1952_4/37/labour_problems__the_giri_approach.pdf|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> The Giri approach emphasizes negotiations between the management and workers as the means for resolving industrial disputes. It holds that the failure of such negotiations should lead not to compulsory adjudication but to further negotiations through conciliation officers.<ref name=\"Durai 392\">{{cite book|author=Pravin Durai|title=Human Resource Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aan1hKH_ejUC&pg=PA392|publisher=Pearson Education India|isbn=978-81-317-6783-2|pages=392\u2013|year=2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Ghodke1985\">{{cite book|author=N. B. Ghodke|title=Encyclopaedic Dictionary of Economics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4_1OU9cVM4YC&pg=PA522|year=1985|publisher=Mittal Publications|pages=522\u2013}}</ref> However, differences with the government over patronage to trade unions, trade union and government opposition to the Giri Approach and the government's decision to reduce the wages of bank employees led him to resign from government in August 1954.<ref name=\"Singh2009\">{{cite book|author=Singh|title=Industrial Relations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gl0tzPYgko8C&pg=PA94|date=1 January 2009|publisher=Excel Books India|isbn=978-81-7446-619-8|pages=94\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Mohanty2004\">{{cite book|author=Manoranjan Mohanty|title=Class, Caste, Gender|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=msyGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA117|date=6 May 2004|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-81-321-0369-1|pages=117\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Mishra2000\">{{cite book|author=Shree Govind Mishra|title=Democracy in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cFs0YSkA4ckC&pg=PA301|year=2000|publisher=Sanbun Publishers|isbn=978-3-473-47305-2|pages=301\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the General Elections of 1957, Giri lost from the [[Parvathipuram (Lok Sabha constituency)|Parvatipuram]] double-member constituency.{{efn|In the General Elections of 1952 and 1957, 83 dual member constituencies electing a member each from the general population and the [[Scheduled Caste]] or [[Scheduled Tribes]] was established. The general candidates including Giri received fewer votes than the Scheduled Caste candidates in Parvatipuram resulting in both the Scheduled Caste candidates being declared elected. Giri unsuccessfully challenged the verdict in court. By the Two Member Constituency (Abolition) Act, 1961 this system of double member constituencies was abolished.<ref>{{cite news|title=Between Red And Blue|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?280573|accessdate=15 January 2015|publisher=Outlook|date=16 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115114557/http://www.outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?280573|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"The Hindu\">{{cite news|title=Have you heard of 2 being elected from one seat? flashback|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/have-you-heard-of-2-being-elected-from-one-seat-flashback/article334429.ece|accessdate=14 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=18 March 2009}}</ref>}}<ref name=\"The Hindu\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=dated March 20, 1957: V.V. Giri defeated|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-miscellaneous/dated-march-20-1957-vv-giri-defeated/article1812948.ece|accessdate=14 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=20 March 2007}}</ref> Giri played an important role in founding the Indian Society of Labour Economics (ISLE).<ref>{{cite web|title=THE INDIAN SOCIETY OF LABOUR ECONOMICS|url=http://crl.du.ac.in/Publication/E-Resources%20in%20Public%20Domain-Final/Economics/Economics%20India/Home%20%20The%20Indian%20Society%20of%20Labour%20Economics.htm|publisher=The Indian Society of Labour Economics|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> In June 1957, he was appointed [[Governor of Uttar Pradesh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=dated June 11, 1957: Governor of UP|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-miscellaneous/dated-june-11-1957-governor-of-up/article1854545.ece|accessdate=14 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=11 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Gubernatorial tenures (1957\u20131967) ===\nBetween 1957\u20131967, Giri served as governor of [[Uttar Pradesh]] (1957\u20131960), [[Kerala]] (1960\u20131965) and [[Karnataka]] (1965\u20131967).<ref name=\"President of India\">[http://vicepresidentofindia.nic.in/giri.asp President of India] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210115524/http://vicepresidentofindia.nic.in/giri.asp |date=10 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==== Governor of Kerala (1960\u20131965) ====\nGiri was sworn in as the [[List of Governors of Kerala|second Governor of Kerala]] on 1 July 1960.<ref>{{cite news|title=R.S. Gavai is new Kerala Governor|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/rs-gavai-is-new-kerala-governor/article1285183.ece|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=27 June 2008}}</ref> As Governor, Giri's active voicing of Kerala's fiscal needs with the [[Planning Commission (India)|Planning Commission]] led to the state being allocated significantly more funds in the Third [[Five Year Plan (India)|Five Year Plan]].<ref name=\"Chatterjee1992\">{{cite book|author=Sibranjan Chatterjee|title=Governor's Role in the Indian Constitution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8UQpnoasCDYC&pg=PA148|date=1 January 1992|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-7099-325-4|pages=148\u2013}}</ref> When defections from the ruling Congress Party reduced the government to a minority, Giri recommended the imposition of [[President's rule|President's Rule]] in Kerala after determining that an alternative government could not be formed.<ref name=\"Srivastava1980\">{{cite book|author=Meera Srivastava|title=Constitutional Crisis in the States in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DAroH5ZqPgsC&pg=PA53|year=1980|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|pages=53\u2013}}</ref> A hung assembly resulted from the elections to the [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]] in 1965. Since no party had a majority and no alliances commanding a majority could be formed, Giri again recommended the dissolution of the assembly and the imposition of President's Rule in the state.<ref name=\"Gandhi2006\">{{cite book|author=Kishor Gandhi|title=India's Date with Destiny: Ranbir Singh Chowdhary : Felicitation Volume|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BlkAf8Pe4GwC&pg=PA65|year=2006|publisher=Allied Publishers|isbn=978-81-7764-932-1|pages=65\u2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Vice president (1967\u20131969) and acting president of India (1969) ===\nGiri was elected the [[List of Vice-Presidents of India|third]] [[Vice President of India|vice president of India]] on 13 May 1967, a post he held for nearly two years till 3 May 1969.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chapter \u2013 4 Presiding Officers of Rajya Sabha and other Parliamentary Functionaries|url=http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-4.pdf|publisher=Rajya Sabha|accessdate=8 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206014203/http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-4.pdf|archive-date=6 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Giri was the first vice president to not complete his full term in office on account of being elevated to the office of the president and was the third vice president to be elected to the presidency.<ref>{{cite news|title=Krishan Kant is first vice-president to die in office|url=http://m.rediff.com/news/2002/jul/27vp1.htm|accessdate=19 January 2015|publisher=Rediff.com|date=27 July 2002}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the death in office of President [[Zakir Hussain (politician)|Zakir Hussain]] on 3 May 1969, Giri was sworn in as acting president the same day.<ref name=\"Singh\">{{cite book|author=K. Natwar Singh|title=Walking With Lions: Tales From A Diplomatic Past|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ecHjAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA13-IA4|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India|isbn=978-93-5029-899-2|pages=13\u2013|date=2012-12-20}}</ref> Giri resigned from his post on 20 July 1969 to contest the presidential elections as an independent candidate.<ref name=\"Bhatia2014\">{{cite book|author=Sudarshan Bhatia|title=His Excellency President of India Pranab Mukherjee|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mtv3AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT59|date=4 March 2014|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books Pvt Ltd|isbn=978-93-5083-645-3|pages=59\u2013}}</ref> Immediately before resigning, Giri, in his capacity as acting president, promulgated an ordinance that nationalised 14 banks and insurance companies.<ref name=\"HewittHewitt2007\">{{cite book|author1=Senior Lecturer in Politics Vernon Hewitt|author2=Vernon Hewitt|title=Political Mobilisation and Democracy in India: States of Emergency|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sh6yVyWM4pwC&pg=PA85|date=5 November 2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-09762-3|pages=85\u2013}}</ref> He was succeeded as acting president by [[Mohammad Hidayatullah]], the [[Chief Justice of India]].{{efn|Following Giri's resignation, the offices of president and vice president became vacant, with the [[Constitution of India]] requiring the Chief Justice of India to act as president. Justice Hidayatullah served as acting president during July \u2013 August 1969. Elected vice president in 1979, he again served as acting president in October 1982. He is the only person in India to have served twice as acting president.<ref name=\"Bhardwaj 1\">{{cite book|author=A. P. Bhardwaj|title=Legal Awareness and Legal Reasoning for the CLAT and LLb Entrance Examinations, 4/e|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RchoBAAAQBAJ&pg=SL1-PA241|isbn=978-93-325-3732-3|pages=1\u2013|year=2014}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news|title=The twice Acting-President|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-in-school/the-twice-actingpresident/article3676405.ece|accessdate=19 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=24 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Presidential election of 1969 ===\nThe election of a new president became a contest between the Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]] and the old guard of the Congress Party known as the Syndicate.<ref>{{cite book|author=John McLeod|title=The History of India|date=2002|publisher=Greenwood Press|page=149|url=https://www.questia.com/read/101360237/the-history-of-india|accessdate=8 January 2015|url-access=subscription |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref> The [[All India Congress Committee]] decided to support [[Neelam Sanjiva Reddy]] as the presidential candidate, disregarding the [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister's]] opposition.<ref name=\"A populist move, a party chasm\">{{cite news|author=Inder Malhotra|title=A populist move, a party chasm|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/a-populist-move-a-party-chasm/99/|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=The Indian Express|date=23 December 2013}}</ref> Giri, who was vice president, resigned and decided to contest as an independent candidate.<ref name=\"A populist move, a party chasm\"/> Prime Minister Gandhi then decided to support him, endorsing a \"vote of conscience\" that allowed Congress legislators to vote for Giri.<ref name=\"Guha2011\">{{cite book|author=Ramachandra Guha|title=India After Gandhi: The History of the World's Largest Democracy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FKepYC6wzwC&pg=PA438|date=10 February 2011|publisher=Pan Macmillan|isbn=978-0-330-54020-9|pages=438\u2013}}</ref> The election, held on 16 August 1969, witnessed a contest between Reddy, Giri and the opposition candidate [[C D Deshmukh]].<ref name=\"KochanekHardgrave2007\">{{cite book|author1=Stanley Kochanek|author2=Robert Hardgrave|title=India: Government and Politics in a Developing Nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pSyRgcSQhuIC&pg=PT82|date=30 January 2007|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-495-00749-4|pages=82\u2013}}</ref> In the closely fought election V V Giri emerged victorious, winning 48.01 per cent of the first preference votes and subsequently getting a majority on counting the second preference votes. In the final tally, Giri had 420,077 votes against the quota of 418,169 votes required to be elected president.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sanjiva Reddy only President elected unopposed|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article3529044.ece|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=15 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Pylee2009\">{{cite book|author=M V Pylee|title=An Introduction To The Constitution Of India, 5E|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zps_kbj-9nsC&pg=PA158|date=1 November 2009|publisher=Vikas Publishing House Pvt Ltd|isbn=978-81-259-1832-5|pages=158\u2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Giri's election, an [[election petition]] was filed in the [[Supreme Court of India]] contesting its validity on the grounds of having used corrupt practices to influence voters. Giri, unusually for an incumbent president of India, chose to appear in person before the Court where he was examined as a witness. The Court ultimately dismissed the petition and upheld Giri's election as president.<ref>{{cite news|title=How VV Giri defended himself|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-how-vv-giri-defended-himself-1106843|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=DNA|date=29 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n== President of India ==\n[[File:State Visits by V V Giri.png|right|thumb|As President of India Giri led 14 state visits to countries in [[South Asia|South]] and [[South East Asia]], the [[Soviet bloc]] and [[Africa]].]]\n\nGiri was sworn in as President of India on 24 August 1969 and held office till 24 August 1974 when he was succeeded by [[Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Presidents |url=http://presidentofindia.nic.in/former-presidents.htm |publisher=The President of India |accessdate=17 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016060850/http://presidentofindia.nic.in/former-presidents.htm |archivedate=16 October 2014 }}</ref> On his election, Giri became the only president to have also been an acting president and the only person to be elected president as an independent candidate.<ref name=\"Bhardwaj 1\"/>\n\nAs president, Giri unquestioningly accepted Prime Minister Indira Gandhi's decision to sack the [[Charan Singh]] ministry in Uttar Pradesh and advised her to go in for early elections in 1971.<ref>{{cite news|title=Past Presidents: Waning power|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/office-of-the-president-a-glamorous-edifice-but-with-a-timorous-reserve-of-real-power/1/391902.html|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=India Today|date=18 October 2013}}</ref> The [[Ordinance (India)|ordinance]] abolishing [[Privy Purse in India|privy purses]] and privileges of the erstwhile rulers of [[Princely state|India's princely states]] was promulgated by Giri after the government's original amendment was defeated in the [[Rajya Sabha]].<ref name=\"Steinberg2008\">{{cite book|author=Blema Steinberg|title=Women in Power: The Personalities and Leadership Styles of Indira Gandhi, Golda Meir, and Margaret Thatcher|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n2R0OAYkcgMC&pg=PA33|date=1 January 2008|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press \u2013 MQUP|isbn=978-0-7735-7502-8|pages=33\u2013}}</ref> His advice to Prime Minister Gandhi against the appointement of [[A.N. Ray]] as the [[Chief Justice of India]] superseding three judges senior to him was ignored by her as was his warning that a crackdown on striking railwaymen would only exacerbate the situation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Emerging evidence|url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mag/2003/01/05/stories/2003010500540200.htm|accessdate=15 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=5 January 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author= Mary Carras|title=Indira Gandhi: In the Crucible of Leadership|date=1979|publisher=Beacon Press|location=Boston|page=172|url=https://www.questia.com/read/96271846/indira-gandhi-in-the-crucible-of-leadership|accessdate=15 January 2015|url-access=subscription |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref> As president, Giri made 14 state visits to 22 countries in [[South Asia|South]] and [[South East Asia]], [[Europe]] and [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DETAILS OF MEDIA PERSONS ACCOMPANYING THE PRESIDENT IN HIS/HER VISITS ABROAD SINCE 1947 TO 2012|url=http://rashtrapatisachivalaya.gov.in/media_abroad.pdf|publisher=The President's Secretariat|accessdate=5 June 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817094728/http://rashtrapatisachivalaya.gov.in/media_abroad.pdf|archivedate=17 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=President's visits undertaken after careful appraisal|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/presidents-visits-undertaken-after-careful-appraisal/article3255825.ece|accessdate=19 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=29 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nGiri is regarded as a president who completely subordinated himself to the prime minister and has been described as a \"Prime Minister\u2019s President\",<ref>{{cite journal|title=Changing Roles of the Presidents of India|journal=Mainstream Weekly|date=17 August 2012|volume=L|url=http://www.mainstreamweekly.net/article3633.html|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> a loyalist president and a [[Rubber stamp (politics)|rubber stamp]] president under whom the independence of the office eroded.<ref name=\"BaakliniDesfosses1997\">{{cite book|author1=Abdo I. Baaklini|author2=Helen Desfosses|title=Designs for Democratic Stability: Studies in Viable Constitutionalism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NFhiXjPle1AC&pg=PA162|date=1 January 1997|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-0052-3|pages=162\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pranab won't be a 'rubber stamp'|url=http://archive.asianage.com/india/pranab-won-t-be-rubber-stamp-935|accessdate=17 January 2015|publisher=The Asian Age|date=23 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=A G Noorani|title=The Parliamentary System in South Asia|journal=Criterion Quarterly|date=4 October 2013|volume=2|issue=3|url=http://www.criterion-quarterly.com/the-parliamentary-system-in-south-asia/|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> When Giri's term ended in 1974, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi chose not to renominate him to the presidency and instead chose Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed, who was elected in the presidential election of 1974.<ref name=\"Ananth\">{{cite book|author=Ananth|title=India Since Independence: Making Sense of Indian Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CBQ7BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA84|isbn=978-81-317-4282-2|pages=84\u2013|year=2008}}</ref>\n\n== Bharat Ratna ==\nGiri was honoured with India's highest civilian award, the [[Bharat Ratna]], in 1975 for his contributions in the area of public affairs.<ref>{{cite web|title=List of recipients of the Bharat Ratna|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/Recipients-BR.pdf|publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=List of all Bharat Ratna award winners|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/list-of-all-bharat-ratna-award-winners-81336|accessdate=17 January 2015|publisher=NDTV|date=24 January 2011}}</ref> As president, Giri had [[suo motu]] conferred the Bharat Ratna on Prime Minister Indira Gandhi in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|title=Awards earned, awards fixed?|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2003/01/19/stories/2003011900251600.htm|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=19 January 2003}}</ref> Giri was in turn conferred the Bharat Ratna in 1975 on the recommendation of Prime Minister Gandhi, in an act seen as a quid pro quo measure.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flashback to time of Nehru Ratna|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1141225/jsp/nation/story_5228.jsp#.VMPXQNKUe9p|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Telegraph|date=25 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bose or Vajpayee: India politicises, then downgrades Bharat Ratna|url=http://www.firstpost.com/politics/bose-or-vajpayee-india-politicises-then-downgrades-bharat-ratna-1659607.html|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=Firstpost|date=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bharat Ratna: It's not for 'useful citizens', it's for politicians and entertainers|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/bharat-ratna-it-s-not-for-useful-citizens-it-s-for-politicians-and-entertainers/article1-1303199.aspx|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Hindustan Times|date=4 January 2015}}</ref> Giri was the fourth of the six Presidents of India to have been conferred the Bharat Ratna (viz. [[Rajendra Prasad]], [[Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan]], [[Zakir Husain (politician)|Zakir Husain]], V.V. Giri, [[Avul Pakir Jainulabdeen Abdul Kalam]] and [[Pranab Mukherjee]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=Awards and acrimony|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/columns/awards-and-acrimony/article5376264.ece|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu Businessline|date=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nGiri died of a [[heart attack]] in [[Madras]] on 24 June 1980.<ref name=\"Lentz2014 2\">{{cite book|author=Harris M. Lentz|title=Heads of States and Governments Since 1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6HKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA379|accessdate=21 June 2018|date=4 February 2014|publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781134264902|pages=379\u2013380}}</ref> He was given a [[state funeral]] the next day and a week-long mourning period was declared by the [[Government of India]].<ref name=\"Kamath2009\">{{cite book|author=M.V. Kamath|title=Journalist's Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7A90vWbKyDEC&pg=PA222 |date=1 November 2009|publisher=Vikas Publishing House Pvt Ltd|isbn=978-0-7069-9026-3|pages=222\u2013}}</ref> Rajya Sabha, of which Giri had been ex-officio chairman as Vice President of India, adjourned for two days as a mark of respect to him.<ref>{{cite book|title=Rajya Sabha at Work \u2013 Chapter 16: Obituary and Other References|page=386|url=http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-16.pdf|accessdate=6 January 2015|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123165001/http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-16.pdf|archivedate=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Commemoration ==\n[[File:VV Giri 1974 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|Giri on a 1974 stamp of India]]\nA [[commemorative postage stamp]] on V.V Giri was released by the [[India Posts|Indian Posts and Telegraphs Department]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|title=Postal Stamp Name : V V Giri|url=http://www.indianpost.com/viewstamp.php/Alpha/V/V.%20V.%20GIRI%20(PRESIDENT%20OF%20INDIA)|publisher=IndianPost|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Stamps 1974|url=http://iic.ac.in/projects/nic/Contrivers/1974.html|publisher=Philately World|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> The [[V. V. Giri National Labour Institute|National Labour Institute]] was renamed in honour of V.V Giri in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|title=V. V. Giri National Labour Institute: History|url=http://www.vvgnli.org/institute/history|publisher=VV Giri National Labour Institute|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> Giri's hometown of Berhampur has a major road, a secondary training school and a market that are named after him.<ref>{{cite news|title=156-year-old school renamed after V. V. Giri|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/156yearold-school-renamed-after-v-v-giri/article3382923.ece|accessdate=9 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nGiri authored ''Industrial Relations'' and ''Labour Problems in Indian Industry'', two popular books on issues of labour in India.<ref name=\"Durai 387\">{{cite book|author=Pravin Durai|title=Human Resource Management: For VTU|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EWQ8BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA387|isbn=978-81-317-9873-7|pages=387\u2013|year=2011}}</ref> His memoirs, published in 1976, are titled ''My Life and Times''.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book|author=V V Giri|title=My Life and Times, Volume 1|date=1976|publisher=Macmillan Company of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=blEKkgEACAAJ|isbn=9780333901335}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n* Commemorative Medal of the [[2,500 year celebration of the Persian Empire|2500th Anniversary of the founding of the Persian Empire]] (14 October 1971)<ref>[http://badraie.com/guests.htm Badraie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305043732/http://badraie.com/guests.htm |date=5 March 2016 }}</ref>\n* King Jigme Singye Investiture Medal (Kingdom of Bhutan, 2 June 1974)<ref>Karma Galay ed. (1999) [http://archiv.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/savifadok/315/1/Coronation.pdf Final Programmes for The Coronation and The Silver Jubilee Celebration]. The Centre for Bhutan Studies</ref>\n* [[Bharat Ratna]] (Republic of India, 1975)<ref name=\"President of India\"/>\n\n== Explanatory notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|V. V. Giri}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/biography/Varahagiri-Venkata-Giri V. V. Giri] at Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\n\n{{Presidents of India}}\n{{IndianVicePresidents}}\n{{Governors of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Governors of Karnataka}}\n{{Bharat Ratna}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Giri, V. V.}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Governors of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Governors of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Governors of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Members of Central Legislative Assembly of India]]\n[[Category:Presidents of India]]\n[[Category:People from Ganjam district]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bharat Ratna]]\n[[Category:Vice-Presidents of India]]\n[[Category:Tamil Nadu ministers]]\n[[Category:Telugu politicians]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:Acting Presidents of India]]\n[[Category:University of Madras alumni]]\n[[Category:Labour ministers of India]]\n[[Category:1st Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fourth President of India}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| name = Varahagiri Venkata Giri\n| image = VV Giri 1974 stamp of India.jpg| caption = V. V. Giri \n| office = [[List of Presidents of India|4th]] [[President of India]]\n| vicepresident = [[Gopal Swarup Pathak]]\n| term_start = 24 August 1969\n| term_end = 24 August 1974\n| predecessor = [[Mohammad Hidayatullah]] <small>(Acting)</small>\n| successor = [[Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Indira Gandhi]]\n| term_start2 = 3 May 1969\n| term_end2 = 20 July 1969\n| predecessor2 = [[Zakir Hussain (politician)|Zakir Hussain]]\n| successor2 = [[Mohammad Hidayatullah]] <small>(Acting)</small>\n| primeminister3 = [[Indira Gandhi]]\n| office3 = [[List of Vice Presidents of India|3rd]] [[Vice President of India]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Indira Gandhi]]\n| president3 = [[Zakir Hussain (politician)|Zakir Hussain]]\n| term_start3 = 13 May 1967\n| term_end3 = 3 May 1969\n| predecessor3 = [[Zakir Hussain (politician)|Zakir Hussain]]\n| successor3 = [[Gopal Swarup Pathak]]\n| office4 = [[List of Governors of Karnataka|Governor of Karnataka]]\n| 1blankname4 = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata4 = [[S. Nijalingappa]]\n| term_start4 = 2 April 1965\n| term_end4 = 13 May 1967\n| predecessor4 = [[Satyawant Mallannah Shrinagesh]]\n| successor4 = [[Gopal Swarup Pathak]]\n| office5 = [[List of Governors of Kerala|Governor of Kerala]]\n| 1blankname5 = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata5 = [[Pattom A. Thanu Pillai|Pattom Thanu Pillai]]<br/>[[R. Sankar]]\n| term_start5 = 1 July 1960\n| term_end5 = 2 April 1965\n| predecessor5 = [[Burgula Ramakrishna Rao]]\n| successor5 = [[Ajit Prasad Jain]]\n| office6 = [[List of Governors of Uttar Pradesh|Governor of Uttar Pradesh]]\n| 1blankname6 = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata6 = [[Sampurnanand]]\n| term_start6 = 10 June 1956\n| term_end6 = 30 June 1960\n| predecessor6 = [[Kanhaiyalal Maneklal Munshi]]\n| successor6 = [[Burgula Ramakrishna Rao]]\n| office7 = [[Minister of Industry|Minister of Labour and Industry]] for [[Madras Presidency]]\n| 1blankname7 = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata7 = [[Tanguturi Prakasam]]\n| term_start7 = 30 April 1946\n| term_end7 = 23 March 1947\n| birth_name = Varahagiri Venkata Giri\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1894|8|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Berhampur]] in [[Odisha]], [[India]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1980|6|24|1894|8|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Madras]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]<br />(now [[Chennai]])\n| party = [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n| spouse = Saraswati Bai (1904\u20131978)\n| relatives =\n*[[Adruti Laxmibai]] (sister)<ref name=\"Participation of Women of Ganjam District in the Freedom Movement of India\">{{cite web |author1=Dasarathi Bhuyan |title=Participation of Women of Ganjam District in the Freedom Movement of India |url=http://magazines.odisha.gov.in/Orissareview/2010/August/engpdf/august%202010.pdf |publisher=Orissa Review |accessdate=27 November 2018 |pages=18\u201320 }}</ref>\n*[[Palagummi Sainath]] (grandson)<ref name=\"cockburn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/cockburn08042005.html |title=Why Indian Farmers Kill Themselves; Why Lange's Photographs are Phony |publisher=Counterpunch.org |date=4 August 2005 |accessdate=29 November 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050807232632/http://www.counterpunch.org/cockburn08042005.html |archivedate=7 August 2005 }}</ref>\n| alma_mater = [[Khallikote College]]<br/>[[University College Dublin]]\n| awards = [[Bharat Ratna]] (1975)\n| signature = Varahagiri Venkatagiri Signature.jpg\n| signature_alt = Varahagiri Venkatagiri Signature in English\n}}\n\n'''Varahagiri Venkata Giri''' {{audio|Vvg.ogg|pronunciation}} (10 August 1894 \u2013 24 June 1980), commonly known as '''V. V. Giri''', was the [[List of Presidents of India|fourth]] [[president of India]] from 24 August 1969 to 24 August 1974.\n\nAs president, Giri was the only person to be elected as an independent candidate.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/bjp-vs-opposition-india-set-to-witness-tightest-presidential-poll-since-1969/story-sZ5LlpWvMBaxPULLoQHZbN.html |title=NDA vs Oppn: India might to witness tightest presidential poll since 1969 |author=Saubhadra Chatterji |date=26 April 2017 |website=[[Hindustan Times]]|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> He was succeeded by [[Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed]] as president in 1974.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/gal.html | title=Gallery of Indian Presidents |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212121818/http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/gal.html |archive-date=12 December 2017 |website=[[Press Information Bureau]] |publisher=Government of India |access-date=21 June 2018 }}</ref> After the end of his full term, Giri was honoured by the [[Government of India]] with the [[Bharat Ratna]] in 1975. Giri died on 24 June 1980. His great grandson V. Giri Shankar is an Advocate of the Madras High Court, Chennai.\n\n==Early life==\nGiri was born in [[Berhampur]], [[Odisha]] to a [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-speaking <ref>https://books.google.co.in/books?id=r2C2InxI0xAC&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72&dq=vv+giri+brahmin&source=bl&ots=o-BA_JrGWG&sig=ACfU3U0mJkPCBkYHTjuv5etqprwj8b7U9Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjIkM6E9q3mAhUWyzgGHeU6B9A4ChDoATACegQIBxAB</ref> family. His father, V. V. Jogayya  Pantulu, was a successful lawyer and political activist of the Indian National Congress.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Great Indian Patriots, Volume 1|author=P. Rajeswar Rao|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1991|isbn=9788170992806|location=India|pages=279\u2013282}}</ref> Giri's mother Subhadramma was active in the national movement in Berhampur during the [[Non Cooperation Movement|Non Cooperation]] and [[Civil Disobedience Movement]]s and was arrested for leading a strike for [[prohibition]] during the Civil Disobedience Movement.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Bina Kumari Sarma|title=Women's Role in the Freedom Movement in South Orissa|journal=Orissa Review|date=August 2010|pages=34\u201335|url=http://orissa.gov.in/e-magazine/Orissareview/2010/August/engpdf/34-38.pdf|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nGiri was married to Saraswati Bai and the couple had 14 children.<ref name=\"Rao1991\">{{cite book|author=P. Rajeswar Rao|title=The Great Indian Patriots|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eTrs9MF9374C&pg=PA278|year=1991|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-7099-280-6|page=282}}</ref>\n\nGiri completed his initial education at the [[Khallikote College]], then affiliated with [[Utkal University]], in Berhampur.<ref>{{cite web|title=Varahagiri Venkata Giri|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/234218/Varahagiri-Venkata-Giri|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> In 1913 he went to Ireland to study law which he did at [[University College Dublin]] and the [[King's Inns|Honourable Society of King's Inns, Dublin]] between 1913\u20131916.<ref>{{cite news|title=University College Dublin announces special scholarships for Indian students|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/university-college-dublin-announces-special-scholarships-for-indian-students/1/328125.html|accessdate=8 January 2015|publisher=India Today|date=6 November 2013}}</ref> Giri was one among the first crop of thirteen Indian students who sat the obligatory year long course at UCD in 1914\u201315. This was a requirement for being called to the Irish Bar through study at the King's Inns. In total, 50 Indian students studied at UCD between 1914 and 1917.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Irish Days, Indian Memories: V. V. Giri and Indian Law Students at University College Dublin, 1913\u20131916|author= Conor Mulvagh|publisher=Irish Academic Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-911024-18-7|location=Sallins|pages=43}}</ref>\n\nGiri and a fellow law student also enrolled to study on the full bachelor of arts course in UCD. Giri studied English, where he was lectured by [[Thomas MacDonagh]], and Political Economy. His lecturer in political economy was the reformer and co-operativist [[Thomas A. Finlay|Thomas A. Finlay SJ]].\n\nDuring the First World War, Giri travelled from Dublin to London and met with [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Gandhi wanted for Giri to join the Imperial war effort as a Red Cross Volunteer. Giri initially acceded to Gandhi's request but later regretted his decision. According to one of Giri's biographers, \"Gandhiji with his characteristic magnanimity relieved Giri of the obligation to join the Red Cross and did not breathe a word about it to anyone.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/gandhi-an-expelled-future-president-and-first-aid-crews-the-indians-of-1916-rising-1.2529440|title=Gandhi, an expelled future president and first aid crews: the Indians of 1916 Rising|author=Conor Mulvagh|date=10 February 2016|work=|newspaper=The Irish Times|access-date=17 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nGiri was active in both Indian and Irish politics during his studies. Along with fellow Indian students he produced a pamphlet documenting the abuse of Indians in South Africa. The pamphlet was intercepted by [[Indian Political Intelligence Office|Indian Political Intelligence]] and resulted in increased police scrutiny of Giri and his fellow students in Dublin.<ref name=\":0\" /> Meanwhile, anonymous articles were written by Indian students for the newspaper of the [[Irish Volunteers]] and in ''The National Student'', a UCD student magazine.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Irish Days, Indian Memories: V. V. Giri and Indian Law Students at University College Dublin, 1913\u20131916|author=Conor Mulvagh|publisher=Irish Academic Press|year=2016 |isbn=978-1-911024-18-7|location=Sallins, Co. Kildare, Ireland|pages=34, 49\u201350|quote=|via=http://irishacademicpress.ie/product/irish-days-indian-memories-v-v-giri-and-indian-law-students-at-university-college-dublin-1913-1916/}}</ref>\n\nHe was suspected of association with prominent ring leaders in the [[Easter Rising|1916 Rising]] including [[James Connolly]], [[Patrick Pearse|PH Pearse]] and the young [[\u00c9amon de Valera]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2005/08/04/why-indian-farmers-kill-themselves-why-lange-s-photographs-are-phony/|title=Why Indian Farmers Kill Themselves; Why Lange's Photographs are Phony|date=25 March 2005|publisher=Counter Punch |author=Alexander Cockburn |accessdate=19 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Bhattacharya2013\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iLxnAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA636|title=NOTHING BUT!|date=December 2013|publisher=Author Solutions|isbn=978-1-4828-1626-6|pages=636\u2013|author=Brigadier Samir Bhattacharya}}</ref><ref name=\"Lentz2014\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RwfKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1538|title=Heads of States and Governments Since 1945|date=4 February 2014|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-134-26497-1|pages=1538\u2013|author=Harris M. Lentz}}</ref> Giri was called to the Irish Bar on 21 June 1916 but he did not complete his studies for BA in UCD.<ref name=\":1\" /> Indian students were subjected to police raids following the 1916 Rising and Giri recounts how he was served with one month's notice to leave Ireland on 1 June 1916.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1916/jun/01/mr-t-a-chettiar-of-madras#S5CV0082P0_19160601_CWA_3|title=MR. T. A. CHETTIAR, OF MADRAS. (Hansard, 1 June 1916)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com|access-date=17 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nUpon returning to India in 1916 Giri enrolled at the [[Madras High Court]].<ref name=\"The Deccan Herald\">{{cite news|title=Worker's leader who turned President|url=http://archive.deccanherald.com/Deccanherald/aug082004/ac3.asp|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Deccan Herald|date=8 August 2004}}</ref> He also became a member of the Congress party, attended its [[Lucknow]] session and joined the [[Home Rule Movement]] of [[Annie Beasant]].<ref name=\"Jai2003 76\">{{cite book|author=Janak Raj Jai|title=Presidents of India, 1950\u20132003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r2C2InxI0xAC&pg=PA76|date=2003|publisher=Regency Publications|isbn=978-81-87498-65-0|page=76}}</ref> Giri abandoned a flourishing legal career in response to [[Mahatma Gandhi|Mahatma Gandhi's]] call for a [[Non-Cooperation Movement]] in 1920.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shekhawat need not compare himself to Giri: Shashi Bhushan|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/shekhawat-need-not-compare-himself-to-giri-shashi-bhushan/article1871463.ece|accessdate=8 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=12 July 2007}}</ref> In 1922, he was arrested for the first time for demonstrating against the sale of liquor shops.<ref name=\"The Deccan Herald\"/>\n\n=== Role in the labour movement ===\nGiri was closely associated with the labour and trade union movement in India throughout his career.<ref name=\"Reminiscences of Gandhiji\">{{cite book|author=Chandrashanker Shukla|title=Reminiscences of Gandhiji|date=March 1951|publisher=Vora & Co.|location=Bombay|page=108 |url=http://krishikosh.egranth.ac.in/bitstream/1/20434/1/G-2493.pdf|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref> Giri was a founding member of the [[All India Railwaymen's Federation]] which was formed in 1923 and served as its general secretary for over a decade.<ref>{{cite web|title=President of India speaking!|url=http://www.taxindiaonline.com/RC2/inside2.php3?filename=bnews_detail.php3&newsid=5743|publisher=taxindiaonline.com|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Chandrasekhar1985\">{{cite book|author=S. Chandrasekhar|title=Dimensions of Socio-political Change in Mysore, 1918\u201340 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zqz9SbueWk4C&pg=PA113|year=1985|publisher=Ashish Publishing House|isbn=978-0-8364-1471-4|pages=113\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"A principled politician\">{{cite news|title=A principled politician |url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/09/23/stories/2002092301370200.htm|accessdate=8 February 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=23 September 2002}}</ref> He was elected president of the [[All India Trade Union Congress]] for the first time in 1926.<ref name=\"Mansingh2006\">{{cite book|author=Surjit Mansingh|title=Historical Dictionary of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6HAeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA240|date=9 May 2006|publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=978-0-8108-6502-0|pages=240\u2013}}</ref> Giri also founded the Bengal Nagpur Railway Association and in 1928 led the workers of the [[Bengal Nagpur Railway]] in a non violent strike for the rights of [[Retrenchment|retrenched]] workers. The strike succeeded in forcing the [[British Raj|British Indian government]] and the management of the railway company to concede the workers' demands and is regarded as a milestone in the labour movement in India.<ref name=\"The Deccan Herald\"/><ref name=\"Reminiscences of Gandhiji\"/><ref name=\"A principled politician\"/>\nIn 1929, the Indian Trade Union Federation (ITUF) was formed by Giri, [[N. M. Joshi]] and others with Giri as the president. The split with the AITUC came about over the issue of cooperating with the Royal Commission on Labour. Giri and the ITUF leadership of liberals decided to cooperate with the Commission while the AITUC decided to boycott it.<ref name=\"Tarique\">{{cite book|author=Mohammad Tarique|title=Modern Indian History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pcKMD9XWyjAC&pg=SA7-PA2|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education|isbn=978-0-07-066030-4|pages=7\u2013}}</ref> The ITUF merged with the AITUC in 1939 and Giri became president of the AITUC for a second time in 1942.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sharit Bhowmik|title=The Labour Movement in India: Fractured Trade Unions and Vulnerable Workers|journal=Rethinking Development and Inequality|date=2013|volume=2|issue=Special Issue|page=86}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=AITUC \u2013 Our Leaders|url=http://aituc.in/leaders.html|publisher=AITUC|accessdate=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206153013/http://aituc.in/leaders.html|archive-date=6 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGiri was the Workers' Delegate of the Indian delegation at the [[International Labour Conference]] of the [[ILO]] in 1927.<ref>{{cite book|title=List of Indian Delegates and Advisers to International Labour Conferences (1919\u20132011)|publisher=V.V.Giri National Labour Institute, Ministry of Labour & Employment|location=NOIDA|url=http://www.vvgnli.org/sites/default/files/publication_files/List-of-Indian-Delegates-Advisors.pdf|accessdate=15 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207151828/http://www.vvgnli.org/sites/default/files/publication_files/List-of-Indian-Delegates-Advisors.pdf|archivedate=7 February 2015}}</ref> At the [[Round Table Conferences (India)|Second Round Table Conference]], Giri was present as a representative of the industrial workers of India.<ref name=\"Reminiscences of Gandhiji\"/> Giri worked towards getting the trade unions to support the freedom movement in India and was twice president of the AITUC which was closely allied with the Indian National Congress.<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\">{{cite book|author=Janak Raj Jai|title=Presidents of India, 1950\u20132003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r2C2InxI0xAC&pg=PA75|date=1 January 2003|publisher=Regency Publications|isbn=978-81-87498-65-0|pages=75\u2013}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral career in British India ==\nGiri became a member of the [[Imperial Legislative Assembly]] in 1934.<ref>Narasingha P. Sil, ''Giri, Varahagiri Venkata (1894\u20131980), trade unionist and president of India'' in ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' (2004)</ref> He remained its member until 1937 and emerged a spokesman for matters of labour and trade unions in the Assembly.<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\"/>\n\nIn the General Elections of 1936, Giri defeated the Raja of Bobbili to become a member of the [[Madras Legislative Assembly]]. Between 1937\u20131939, he was Minister for Labour and Industry in the Congress government headed by [[C Rajagopalachari]].<ref name=\"Chaurasia2002\">{{cite book|author=Radhey Shyam Chaurasia|title=History of Modern India, 1707 A. D. to 2000 A. D|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MS_jrForJOoC&pg=PA300|date=1 January 2002 |publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|isbn=978-81-269-0085-5|pages=300\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Gandhi1997\">{{cite book|author=Rajmohan Gandhi|title=Rajaji: A Life|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JjPHeRd7_UYC&pg=PA171|year=1997|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-026967-3|pages=171\u2013}}</ref> Giri was appointed Governor of the National Planning Committee of the Indian National Congress in 1938. In 1939, the Congress ministries resigned in protest against the British decision to make India a party in the [[Second World War]]. Having returned to the labour movement, Giri was arrested and spent 15 months in prison till March 1941.<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\"/>\n\nFollowing the launch of the [[Quit India Movement]], Giri was imprisoned again by the colonial government in 1942.<ref name=\"GroverArora1994\">{{cite book|author1=Verinder Grover|author2=Ranjana Arora|title=Constitutional Schemes and Political Development in India: Towards Transfer of Power |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBCd9ZKzbUUC&pg=PA8|date=1 January 1994|publisher=Deep & Deep Publications|isbn=978-81-7100-539-0|pages=8\u2013}}</ref> He remained in prison when the AITUC met in [[Nagpur]] in 1943 where he was the president elect.<ref name=\"Singh1981\">{{cite book|author=Viv Bahadour Singh|title=Economic History of India: 1857\u20131956|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xeJEXFnGS6AC&pg=PA590|year=1981|publisher=Allied Publishers|pages=590\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Economic History of India: 1857\u20131956|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xeJEXFnGS6AC&pg=PA590|publisher=Allied Publishers|pages=590\u2013}}</ref> Giri served his sentence in the [[Vellore]] and [[Amravati|Amaravathi]] prisons.<ref name=\"Reddy2003\">{{cite book|author=A. Ranga Reddy|title=The State of Rayalaseema |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_g9T8UoCeO4C&pg=PA373|year=2003|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-7099-814-3|pages=373\u2013}}</ref> Giri remained in prison for three years, his longest sentence, until his release in 1945.<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\"/>\n\nIn the [[1946 Madras legislative assembly election|General Elections of 1946]], Giri was reelected to the Madras Legislative Assembly and became a minister again in charge of the labour portfolio under [[T. Prakasam]].<ref name=\"Jai2003 75\"/>\n\n== Career in independent India ==\nFrom 1947 to 1951, Giri served as India's first High Commissioner to [[Ceylon]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nirupama Rao presents credentials to Chandrika|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2004/09/18/stories/2004091807611300.htm|accessdate=8 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=18 September 2004}}</ref> In the [[General elections in India|General Elections of 1951]], he was elected to the [[1st Lok Sabha]] from [[Pathapatnam]] Lok Sabha Constituency in the [[Madras State]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Key Highlights of General Elections, 1951 to the First Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|location=New Delhi|page=15|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1951/VOL_1_51_LS.PDF|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Union Minister for Labour (1952\u20131954) ===\nOn being elected to Parliament, Giri was appointed Minister of Labour in 1952.<ref name=\"Hensman2013\">{{cite book|author=Rohini Hensman|title=Workers, Unions, and Global Capitalism: Lessons from India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ruusCMIQw7EC&pg=PT75|date=20 August 2013|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-51956-4|pages=75\u2013}}</ref> His policy initiatives as minister gave rise to the ''Giri Approach'' in industrial dispute resolution.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Labour Problems \u2014 The \"Giri Approach \"|journal=The Economic Weekly|date=13 September 1952|page=951|url=http://www.epw.in/system/files/pdf/1952_4/37/labour_problems__the_giri_approach.pdf|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> The Giri approach emphasizes negotiations between the management and workers as the means for resolving industrial disputes. It holds that the failure of such negotiations should lead not to compulsory adjudication but to further negotiations through conciliation officers.<ref name=\"Durai 392\">{{cite book|author=Pravin Durai|title=Human Resource Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aan1hKH_ejUC&pg=PA392|publisher=Pearson Education India|isbn=978-81-317-6783-2|pages=392\u2013|year=2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Ghodke1985\">{{cite book|author=N. B. Ghodke|title=Encyclopaedic Dictionary of Economics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4_1OU9cVM4YC&pg=PA522|year=1985|publisher=Mittal Publications|pages=522\u2013}}</ref> However, differences with the government over patronage to trade unions, trade union and government opposition to the Giri Approach and the government's decision to reduce the wages of bank employees led him to resign from government in August 1954.<ref name=\"Singh2009\">{{cite book|author=Singh|title=Industrial Relations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gl0tzPYgko8C&pg=PA94|date=1 January 2009|publisher=Excel Books India|isbn=978-81-7446-619-8|pages=94\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Mohanty2004\">{{cite book|author=Manoranjan Mohanty|title=Class, Caste, Gender|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=msyGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA117|date=6 May 2004|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-81-321-0369-1|pages=117\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Mishra2000\">{{cite book|author=Shree Govind Mishra|title=Democracy in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cFs0YSkA4ckC&pg=PA301|year=2000|publisher=Sanbun Publishers|isbn=978-3-473-47305-2|pages=301\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the General Elections of 1957, Giri lost from the [[Parvathipuram (Lok Sabha constituency)|Parvatipuram]] double-member constituency.{{efn|In the General Elections of 1952 and 1957, 83 dual member constituencies electing a member each from the general population and the [[Scheduled Caste]] or [[Scheduled Tribes]] was established. The general candidates including Giri received fewer votes than the Scheduled Caste candidates in Parvatipuram resulting in both the Scheduled Caste candidates being declared elected. Giri unsuccessfully challenged the verdict in court. By the Two Member Constituency (Abolition) Act, 1961 this system of double member constituencies was abolished.<ref>{{cite news|title=Between Red And Blue|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?280573|accessdate=15 January 2015|publisher=Outlook|date=16 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115114557/http://www.outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?280573|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"The Hindu\">{{cite news|title=Have you heard of 2 being elected from one seat? flashback|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/have-you-heard-of-2-being-elected-from-one-seat-flashback/article334429.ece|accessdate=14 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=18 March 2009}}</ref>}}<ref name=\"The Hindu\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=dated March 20, 1957: V.V. Giri defeated|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-miscellaneous/dated-march-20-1957-vv-giri-defeated/article1812948.ece|accessdate=14 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=20 March 2007}}</ref> Giri played an important role in founding the Indian Society of Labour Economics (ISLE).<ref>{{cite web|title=THE INDIAN SOCIETY OF LABOUR ECONOMICS|url=http://crl.du.ac.in/Publication/E-Resources%20in%20Public%20Domain-Final/Economics/Economics%20India/Home%20%20The%20Indian%20Society%20of%20Labour%20Economics.htm|publisher=The Indian Society of Labour Economics|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> In June 1957, he was appointed [[Governor of Uttar Pradesh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=dated June 11, 1957: Governor of UP|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-miscellaneous/dated-june-11-1957-governor-of-up/article1854545.ece|accessdate=14 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=11 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Gubernatorial tenures (1957\u20131967) ===\nBetween 1957\u20131967, Giri served as governor of [[Uttar Pradesh]] (1957\u20131960), [[Kerala]] (1960\u20131965) and [[Karnataka]] (1965\u20131967).<ref name=\"President of India\">[http://vicepresidentofindia.nic.in/giri.asp President of India] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210115524/http://vicepresidentofindia.nic.in/giri.asp |date=10 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==== Governor of Kerala (1960\u20131965) ====\nGiri was sworn in as the [[List of Governors of Kerala|second Governor of Kerala]] on 1 July 1960.<ref>{{cite news|title=R.S. Gavai is new Kerala Governor|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/rs-gavai-is-new-kerala-governor/article1285183.ece|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=27 June 2008}}</ref> As Governor, Giri's active voicing of Kerala's fiscal needs with the [[Planning Commission (India)|Planning Commission]] led to the state being allocated significantly more funds in the Third [[Five Year Plan (India)|Five Year Plan]].<ref name=\"Chatterjee1992\">{{cite book|author=Sibranjan Chatterjee|title=Governor's Role in the Indian Constitution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8UQpnoasCDYC&pg=PA148|date=1 January 1992|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-7099-325-4|pages=148\u2013}}</ref> When defections from the ruling Congress Party reduced the government to a minority, Giri recommended the imposition of [[President's rule|President's Rule]] in Kerala after determining that an alternative government could not be formed.<ref name=\"Srivastava1980\">{{cite book|author=Meera Srivastava|title=Constitutional Crisis in the States in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DAroH5ZqPgsC&pg=PA53|year=1980|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|pages=53\u2013}}</ref> A hung assembly resulted from the elections to the [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]] in 1965. Since no party had a majority and no alliances commanding a majority could be formed, Giri again recommended the dissolution of the assembly and the imposition of President's Rule in the state.<ref name=\"Gandhi2006\">{{cite book|author=Kishor Gandhi|title=India's Date with Destiny: Ranbir Singh Chowdhary : Felicitation Volume|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BlkAf8Pe4GwC&pg=PA65|year=2006|publisher=Allied Publishers|isbn=978-81-7764-932-1|pages=65\u2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Vice president (1967\u20131969) and acting president of India (1969) ===\nGiri was elected the [[List of Vice-Presidents of India|third]] [[Vice President of India|vice president of India]] on 13 May 1967, a post he held for nearly two years till 3 May 1969.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chapter \u2013 4 Presiding Officers of Rajya Sabha and other Parliamentary Functionaries|url=http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-4.pdf|publisher=Rajya Sabha|accessdate=8 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206014203/http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-4.pdf|archive-date=6 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Giri was the first vice president to not complete his full term in office on account of being elevated to the office of the president and was the third vice president to be elected to the presidency.<ref>{{cite news|title=Krishan Kant is first vice-president to die in office|url=http://m.rediff.com/news/2002/jul/27vp1.htm|accessdate=19 January 2015|publisher=Rediff.com|date=27 July 2002}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the death in office of President [[Zakir Hussain (politician)|Zakir Hussain]] on 3 May 1969, Giri was sworn in as acting president the same day.<ref name=\"Singh\">{{cite book|author=K. Natwar Singh|title=Walking With Lions: Tales From A Diplomatic Past|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ecHjAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA13-IA4|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India|isbn=978-93-5029-899-2|pages=13\u2013|date=2012-12-20}}</ref> Giri resigned from his post on 20 July 1969 to contest the presidential elections as an independent candidate.<ref name=\"Bhatia2014\">{{cite book|author=Sudarshan Bhatia|title=His Excellency President of India Pranab Mukherjee|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mtv3AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT59|date=4 March 2014|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books Pvt Ltd|isbn=978-93-5083-645-3|pages=59\u2013}}</ref> Immediately before resigning, Giri, in his capacity as acting president, promulgated an ordinance that nationalised 14 banks and insurance companies.<ref name=\"HewittHewitt2007\">{{cite book|author1=Senior Lecturer in Politics Vernon Hewitt|author2=Vernon Hewitt|title=Political Mobilisation and Democracy in India: States of Emergency|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sh6yVyWM4pwC&pg=PA85|date=5 November 2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-09762-3|pages=85\u2013}}</ref> He was succeeded as acting president by [[Mohammad Hidayatullah]], the [[Chief Justice of India]].{{efn|Following Giri's resignation, the offices of president and vice president became vacant, with the [[Constitution of India]] requiring the Chief Justice of India to act as president. Justice Hidayatullah served as acting president during July \u2013 August 1969. Elected vice president in 1979, he again served as acting president in October 1982. He is the only person in India to have served twice as acting president.<ref name=\"Bhardwaj 1\">{{cite book|author=A. P. Bhardwaj|title=Legal Awareness and Legal Reasoning for the CLAT and LLb Entrance Examinations, 4/e|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RchoBAAAQBAJ&pg=SL1-PA241|isbn=978-93-325-3732-3|pages=1\u2013|year=2014}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news|title=The twice Acting-President|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-in-school/the-twice-actingpresident/article3676405.ece|accessdate=19 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=24 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Presidential election of 1969 ===\nThe election of a new president became a contest between the Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]] and the old guard of the Congress Party known as the Syndicate.<ref>{{cite book|author=John McLeod|title=The History of India|date=2002|publisher=Greenwood Press|page=149|url=https://www.questia.com/read/101360237/the-history-of-india|accessdate=8 January 2015|url-access=subscription |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref> The [[All India Congress Committee]] decided to support [[Neelam Sanjiva Reddy]] as the presidential candidate, disregarding the [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister's]] opposition.<ref name=\"A populist move, a party chasm\">{{cite news|author=Inder Malhotra|title=A populist move, a party chasm|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/a-populist-move-a-party-chasm/99/|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=The Indian Express|date=23 December 2013}}</ref> Giri, who was vice president, resigned and decided to contest as an independent candidate.<ref name=\"A populist move, a party chasm\"/> Prime Minister Gandhi then decided to support him, endorsing a \"vote of conscience\" that allowed Congress legislators to vote for Giri.<ref name=\"Guha2011\">{{cite book|author=Ramachandra Guha|title=India After Gandhi: The History of the World's Largest Democracy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FKepYC6wzwC&pg=PA438|date=10 February 2011|publisher=Pan Macmillan|isbn=978-0-330-54020-9|pages=438\u2013}}</ref> The election, held on 16 August 1969, witnessed a contest between Reddy, Giri and the opposition candidate [[C D Deshmukh]].<ref name=\"KochanekHardgrave2007\">{{cite book|author1=Stanley Kochanek|author2=Robert Hardgrave|title=India: Government and Politics in a Developing Nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pSyRgcSQhuIC&pg=PT82|date=30 January 2007|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-495-00749-4|pages=82\u2013}}</ref> In the closely fought election V V Giri emerged victorious, winning 48.01 per cent of the first preference votes and subsequently getting a majority on counting the second preference votes. In the final tally, Giri had 420,077 votes against the quota of 418,169 votes required to be elected president.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sanjiva Reddy only President elected unopposed|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article3529044.ece|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=15 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Pylee2009\">{{cite book|author=M V Pylee|title=An Introduction To The Constitution Of India, 5E|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zps_kbj-9nsC&pg=PA158|date=1 November 2009|publisher=Vikas Publishing House Pvt Ltd|isbn=978-81-259-1832-5|pages=158\u2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Giri's election, an [[election petition]] was filed in the [[Supreme Court of India]] contesting its validity on the grounds of having used corrupt practices to influence voters. Giri, unusually for an incumbent president of India, chose to appear in person before the Court where he was examined as a witness. The Court ultimately dismissed the petition and upheld Giri's election as president.<ref>{{cite news|title=How VV Giri defended himself|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-how-vv-giri-defended-himself-1106843|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=DNA|date=29 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n== President of India ==\n[[File:State Visits by V V Giri.png|right|thumb|As President of India Giri led 14 state visits to countries in [[South Asia|South]] and [[South East Asia]], the [[Soviet bloc]] and [[Africa]].]]\n\nGiri was sworn in as President of India on 24 August 1969 and held office till 24 August 1974 when he was succeeded by [[Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Presidents |url=http://presidentofindia.nic.in/former-presidents.htm |publisher=The President of India |accessdate=17 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016060850/http://presidentofindia.nic.in/former-presidents.htm |archivedate=16 October 2014 }}</ref> On his election, Giri became the only president to have also been an acting president and the only person to be elected president as an independent candidate.<ref name=\"Bhardwaj 1\"/>\n\nAs president, Giri unquestioningly accepted Prime Minister Indira Gandhi's decision to sack the [[Charan Singh]] ministry in Uttar Pradesh and advised her to go in for early elections in 1971.<ref>{{cite news|title=Past Presidents: Waning power|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/office-of-the-president-a-glamorous-edifice-but-with-a-timorous-reserve-of-real-power/1/391902.html|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=India Today|date=18 October 2013}}</ref> The [[Ordinance (India)|ordinance]] abolishing [[Privy Purse in India|privy purses]] and privileges of the erstwhile rulers of [[Princely state|India's princely states]] was promulgated by Giri after the government's original amendment was defeated in the [[Rajya Sabha]].<ref name=\"Steinberg2008\">{{cite book|author=Blema Steinberg|title=Women in Power: The Personalities and Leadership Styles of Indira Gandhi, Golda Meir, and Margaret Thatcher|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n2R0OAYkcgMC&pg=PA33|date=1 January 2008|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press \u2013 MQUP|isbn=978-0-7735-7502-8|pages=33\u2013}}</ref> His advice to Prime Minister Gandhi against the appointement of [[A.N. Ray]] as the [[Chief Justice of India]] superseding three judges senior to him was ignored by her as was his warning that a crackdown on striking railwaymen would only exacerbate the situation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Emerging evidence|url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mag/2003/01/05/stories/2003010500540200.htm|accessdate=15 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=5 January 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author= Mary Carras|title=Indira Gandhi: In the Crucible of Leadership|date=1979|publisher=Beacon Press|location=Boston|page=172|url=https://www.questia.com/read/96271846/indira-gandhi-in-the-crucible-of-leadership|accessdate=15 January 2015|url-access=subscription |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref> As president, Giri made 14 state visits to 22 countries in [[South Asia|South]] and [[South East Asia]], [[Europe]] and [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DETAILS OF MEDIA PERSONS ACCOMPANYING THE PRESIDENT IN HIS/HER VISITS ABROAD SINCE 1947 TO 2012|url=http://rashtrapatisachivalaya.gov.in/media_abroad.pdf|publisher=The President's Secretariat|accessdate=5 June 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817094728/http://rashtrapatisachivalaya.gov.in/media_abroad.pdf|archivedate=17 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=President's visits undertaken after careful appraisal|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/presidents-visits-undertaken-after-careful-appraisal/article3255825.ece|accessdate=19 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=29 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nGiri is regarded as a president who completely subordinated himself to the prime minister and has been described as a \"Prime Minister\u2019s President\",<ref>{{cite journal|title=Changing Roles of the Presidents of India|journal=Mainstream Weekly|date=17 August 2012|volume=L|url=http://www.mainstreamweekly.net/article3633.html|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> a loyalist president and a [[Rubber stamp (politics)|rubber stamp]] president under whom the independence of the office eroded.<ref name=\"BaakliniDesfosses1997\">{{cite book|author1=Abdo I. Baaklini|author2=Helen Desfosses|title=Designs for Democratic Stability: Studies in Viable Constitutionalism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NFhiXjPle1AC&pg=PA162|date=1 January 1997|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-0052-3|pages=162\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pranab won't be a 'rubber stamp'|url=http://archive.asianage.com/india/pranab-won-t-be-rubber-stamp-935|accessdate=17 January 2015|publisher=The Asian Age|date=23 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=A G Noorani|title=The Parliamentary System in South Asia|journal=Criterion Quarterly|date=4 October 2013|volume=2|issue=3|url=http://www.criterion-quarterly.com/the-parliamentary-system-in-south-asia/|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> When Giri's term ended in 1974, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi chose not to renominate him to the presidency and instead chose Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed, who was elected in the presidential election of 1974.<ref name=\"Ananth\">{{cite book|author=Ananth|title=India Since Independence: Making Sense of Indian Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CBQ7BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA84|isbn=978-81-317-4282-2|pages=84\u2013|year=2008}}</ref>\n\n== Bharat Ratna ==\nGiri was honoured with India's highest civilian award, the [[Bharat Ratna]], in 1975 for his contributions in the area of public affairs.<ref>{{cite web|title=List of recipients of the Bharat Ratna|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/Recipients-BR.pdf|publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=List of all Bharat Ratna award winners|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/list-of-all-bharat-ratna-award-winners-81336|accessdate=17 January 2015|publisher=NDTV|date=24 January 2011}}</ref> As president, Giri had [[suo motu]] conferred the Bharat Ratna on Prime Minister Indira Gandhi in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|title=Awards earned, awards fixed?|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2003/01/19/stories/2003011900251600.htm|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=19 January 2003}}</ref> Giri was in turn conferred the Bharat Ratna in 1975 on the recommendation of Prime Minister Gandhi, in an act seen as a quid pro quo measure.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flashback to time of Nehru Ratna|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1141225/jsp/nation/story_5228.jsp#.VMPXQNKUe9p|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Telegraph|date=25 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bose or Vajpayee: India politicises, then downgrades Bharat Ratna|url=http://www.firstpost.com/politics/bose-or-vajpayee-india-politicises-then-downgrades-bharat-ratna-1659607.html|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=Firstpost|date=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bharat Ratna: It's not for 'useful citizens', it's for politicians and entertainers|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/bharat-ratna-it-s-not-for-useful-citizens-it-s-for-politicians-and-entertainers/article1-1303199.aspx|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Hindustan Times|date=4 January 2015}}</ref> Giri was the fourth of the six Presidents of India to have been conferred the Bharat Ratna (viz. [[Rajendra Prasad]], [[Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan]], [[Zakir Husain (politician)|Zakir Husain]], V.V. Giri, [[Avul Pakir Jainulabdeen Abdul Kalam]] and [[Pranab Mukherjee]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=Awards and acrimony|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/columns/awards-and-acrimony/article5376264.ece|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu Businessline|date=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nGiri died of a [[heart attack]] in [[Madras]] on 24 June 1980.<ref name=\"Lentz2014 2\">{{cite book|author=Harris M. Lentz|title=Heads of States and Governments Since 1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6HKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA379|accessdate=21 June 2018|date=4 February 2014|publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781134264902|pages=379\u2013380}}</ref> He was given a [[state funeral]] the next day and a week-long mourning period was declared by the [[Government of India]].<ref name=\"Kamath2009\">{{cite book|author=M.V. Kamath|title=Journalist's Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7A90vWbKyDEC&pg=PA222 |date=1 November 2009|publisher=Vikas Publishing House Pvt Ltd|isbn=978-0-7069-9026-3|pages=222\u2013}}</ref> Rajya Sabha, of which Giri had been ex-officio chairman as Vice President of India, adjourned for two days as a mark of respect to him.<ref>{{cite book|title=Rajya Sabha at Work \u2013 Chapter 16: Obituary and Other References|page=386|url=http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-16.pdf|accessdate=6 January 2015|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123165001/http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/rsat_work/chapter-16.pdf|archivedate=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Commemoration ==\n[[File:VV Giri 1974 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|Giri on a 1974 stamp of India]]\nA [[commemorative postage stamp]] on V.V Giri was released by the [[India Posts|Indian Posts and Telegraphs Department]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|title=Postal Stamp Name : V V Giri|url=http://www.indianpost.com/viewstamp.php/Alpha/V/V.%20V.%20GIRI%20(PRESIDENT%20OF%20INDIA)|publisher=IndianPost|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Stamps 1974|url=http://iic.ac.in/projects/nic/Contrivers/1974.html|publisher=Philately World|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> The [[V. V. Giri National Labour Institute|National Labour Institute]] was renamed in honour of V.V Giri in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|title=V. V. Giri National Labour Institute: History|url=http://www.vvgnli.org/institute/history|publisher=VV Giri National Labour Institute|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> Giri's hometown of Berhampur has a major road, a secondary training school and a market that are named after him.<ref>{{cite news|title=156-year-old school renamed after V. V. Giri|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/156yearold-school-renamed-after-v-v-giri/article3382923.ece|accessdate=9 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu|date=4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nGiri authored ''Industrial Relations'' and ''Labour Problems in Indian Industry'', two popular books on issues of labour in India.<ref name=\"Durai 387\">{{cite book|author=Pravin Durai|title=Human Resource Management: For VTU|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EWQ8BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA387|isbn=978-81-317-9873-7|pages=387\u2013|year=2011}}</ref> His memoirs, published in 1976, are titled ''My Life and Times''.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book|author=V V Giri|title=My Life and Times, Volume 1|date=1976|publisher=Macmillan Company of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=blEKkgEACAAJ|isbn=9780333901335}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n* Commemorative Medal of the [[2,500 year celebration of the Persian Empire|2500th Anniversary of the founding of the Persian Empire]] (14 October 1971)<ref>[http://badraie.com/guests.htm Badraie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305043732/http://badraie.com/guests.htm |date=5 March 2016 }}</ref>\n* King Jigme Singye Investiture Medal (Kingdom of Bhutan, 2 June 1974)<ref>Karma Galay ed. (1999) [http://archiv.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/savifadok/315/1/Coronation.pdf Final Programmes for The Coronation and The Silver Jubilee Celebration]. The Centre for Bhutan Studies</ref>\n* [[Bharat Ratna]] (Republic of India, 1975)<ref name=\"President of India\"/>\n\n== Explanatory notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|V. V. Giri}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/biography/Varahagiri-Venkata-Giri V. V. Giri] at Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\n\n{{Presidents of India}}\n{{IndianVicePresidents}}\n{{Governors of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Governors of Karnataka}}\n{{Bharat Ratna}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Giri, V. V.}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Governors of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Governors of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Governors of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Members of Central Legislative Assembly of India]]\n[[Category:Presidents of India]]\n[[Category:People from Ganjam district]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bharat Ratna]]\n[[Category:Vice-Presidents of India]]\n[[Category:Tamil Nadu ministers]]\n[[Category:Telugu politicians]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:Acting Presidents of India]]\n[[Category:University of Madras alumni]]\n[[Category:Labour ministers of India]]\n[[Category:1st Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "name_user": "122.169.215.127", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eElectoral career in British India)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V._V._Giri"}
{"title_page": "The Hidden Messages in Water", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name              = The Hidden Messages in Water\n| image             = The_hidden_message_in_water.png\n| author            = [[Masaru Emoto]]\n| country           = United States\n| language          = English\n| genre             = Body Mind & Spirit; Pseudoscience\n| publisher         = Beyond Words Pub.\n| release_date      = 2004\n| media_type        = Print\n| pages             = 159\n| isbn              = 978-1-58-270114-1\n}}\n\n== Introduction ==\n[[The Hidden Messages In Water|''The Hidden Messages In Water'']] is a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times Bestseller]] book, written by [[Masaru Emoto]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Hidden-Messages-in-Water/Masaru-Emoto/9780743289801|title=Hidden Messages in Water|date=2005-09-20|isbn=978-0-7432-8980-1|language=en}}</ref>. The book was published in the year 2005 and focuses on a [[pseudoscience]] hypotheses that the molecular structure of water changes by the presence of [[human consciousness]] nearby<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.redorbit.com/news/science/1144934/masaru_emotos_wonderful_world_of_water/|title=Masaru Emoto's Wonderful World of Water|date=2007-11-15|website=Redorbit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>. The book has therefore been translated into twenty four languages<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.co.uk/books/The-Hidden-Messages-in-Water/Masaru-Emoto/9781451656855|title=The Hidden Messages in Water|date=2011-07-05|isbn=978-1-4516-5685-5|language=en}}</ref>.\n\n==Background==\n\n[[Masaru Emoto]] was a Japanese author who broached the theory of a change in the molecular structure of water as a result of human\u2019s subconscious or conscious thoughts. Emoto made use of articulate experiments and diagrams to back his theory. Many researchers like biologist Tyler Volk, physician Harriet A. Hall<ref name=\":0\" />, and biochemist William Reville have often claimed that Emoto\u2019s findings fall under the Pseudoscience dynamic, a branch of science which has not found much validation from the prudent minds<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/the-pseudoscience-of-creating-beautiful-or-ugly-water-1.574583|title=The pseudoscience of creating beautiful (or ugly) water|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>. Masaru Emoto has also been regarded as the \u2018Doctor of alternative medicine\u2019 by some sources<ref name=\":1\" />.\n\n==Content==\n\nEmoto has used high speed photography and carefully propounded diagrammatic representation to elucidate the crystal formation in frozen water contingent on the nature of thoughts, the water was exposed to<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyom.com/cgi-bin/display/librarydisplay.cgi?lid=301|title=DailyOM - The Hidden Messages in Water by Masaru Emoto|website=www.dailyom.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>. The experiments presented in the book talks about formation of clear and snowflake shaped crystals in water which was claimed to be exposed to positive and lovable thoughts<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Radin|first=Dean|last2=Hayssen|first2=Gail|last3=Emoto|first3=Masaru|last4=Kizu|first4=Takashige|date=2006-09-01|title=Double-Blind Test of the Effects of Distant Intention on Water Crystal Formation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1550830706003272|journal=EXPLORE|language=en|volume=2|issue=5|pages=408\u2013411|doi=10.1016/j.explore.2006.06.004|issn=1550-8307}}</ref>. On the contrary, Emoto claims that crystal formation in water which was exposed to negative and abominable thoughts exhibited an asymmetric and unruly pattern. The book tries to suggest the idea that water might be highly reflective of its surroundings and could be used to impart health and positivity around<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.storytel.com/in/en/books/80391-The-Hidden-Messages-in-Water|title=The Hidden Messages in Water|website=www.storytel.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>.\n==Reception==\n\nThe book received a rather mixed attention. Some people hailed the findings demonstrated in the book and spoke greatly about its relevance. \u201cThe Hidden Messages in Water is magnificent. Through his genius photography and superb scientific skill, Dr. Masaru Emoto has created a book that is truly a mystical treasure.\u201d Said Caroline M. Myss, author of Sacred Contracts and Anatomy of the Spirit. Whereas, Stephen Kiesling in Spirituality & Health Magazine wrote \"What he is saying has nothing to do with science as I know it.\" And \"Perhaps Emoto is an evangelist who values the message of his images more than the particulars of science; nevertheless, this spiritual teacher might focus his future practice less on gratitude and more on honesty\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spirituality-health.com/articles-latest-message-water-dr-emoto-spiritual-madoff/|title=Latest Message from Water: Is Dr. Emoto a Spiritual Madoff? {{!}} Spirituality & Health|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>. Noelle C. Nelson, PhD and co-author of The Power of Appreciation said that \u201cDr. Emoto's work with water beautifully illustrates the healing power of love and gratitude.\u201d On being New York Times Bestseller, literary critic Dwight Garner wrote in The New York Times Book Review that \u201cit was one of those \u201chead-scratchers\" that made him question the sanity of the reading public.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/463050722|title=Want rain? It's all in the brain, expert says|last=Previch|first=Chad|date=January 21, 2006|website=ProQuest|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Critical reception and skepticism ==\nEmoto\u2019s work has managed to attract a lot of skepticism and critique. His work has shown considerable imprints of Pseudoscience and hence the credibility of his claims are constantly under question by the scientific community. According to a report published in \u201cit is very unlikely that there is any reality behind Emoto\u2019s claims. A triple blind study of these claims failed to show any effect. Also, the phenomenon he describes has never been published in a peer reviewed science journal, which almost certainly means that the effect cannot be demonstrated under controlled conditions.\u201d<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/the-pseudoscience-of-creating-beautiful-or-ugly-water-1.574583|title=The pseudoscience of creating beautiful (or ugly) water|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Skeptics also believe that The Hidden Messages in Water appeals to that class of people who get fascinated by \u201cnew age science\u201d like out of body experience and Chakra healing. There apparently is a huge fan base for these theories said William revile who is a professor of biochemistry at UCC.<ref name=\":2\" /><br />\n\n== More from the Author ==\n\n* \u6c34\u304b\u3089\u306e\u4f1d\u8a00: \u4e16\u754c\u521d!! \u6c34\u306e\u7d50\u6676\u5199\u771f\u96c6 (Mizu kara no dengon: sekaihatsu!! mizu no kessh\u014d shashinsh\u016b) [Messages from Water] (in Japanese). 1. Tokyo: Hado. 1999. <nowiki>ISBN 9784939098000</nowiki>.\n* English edition: The Message from Water: The Message from Water is Telling Us to Take a Look at Ourselves. 1. Hado. 2000. <nowiki>ISBN 9784939098000</nowiki>.\n* \u6c34\u304b\u3089\u306e\u4f1d\u8a00\uff1a \u4e16\u754c\u521d\uff01\uff01\u6c34\u306e\u6c37\u7d50\u7d50\u6676\u5199\u771f\u96c6\u4eca\u65e5\u3082\u6c34\u306b\u3042\u308a\u304c\u3068\u3046 (Mizu kara no dengon: sekaihatsu!! mizu no kessh\u014d shashinsh\u016b) [The Messages from Water] (in Japanese). 2. Tokyo: Hado. 2001. <nowiki>ISBN 9784939098048</nowiki>.\n* English edition: The Message from Water. 2. Hado. 2001. <nowiki>ISBN 9784939098048</nowiki>.\n* \u6c34\u304c\u4f1d\u3048\u308b\u611b\u306e\u304b\u305f\u3061 (Mizu ga tsutaeru ai no katachi) (in Japanese). Tokyo: Tokuma Shoten. 2003. <nowiki>ISBN 9784198617509</nowiki>.\n* English edition: The Shape of Love: Discovering Who We Are, Where We Came From, and Where We are Going. New York: Doubleday. 2007. <nowiki>ISBN 9780385518376</nowiki>.\n* Love Thyself: The Message from Water III. Carlsbad, CA: Hay House. 2004. <nowiki>ISBN 9781401908997</nowiki>.\n* \u6c34\u53ef\u4ee5\u6539\u8b8a\u6211\u751f\u547d\u00a0: \"\u611b\u548c\u611f\u8b1d\"\u7684\u5fc3\u60c5\u53ef\u4ee5\u5275\u9020\u7a4d\u6975\u7684\u80fd\u91cf (Shui ke yi gai bian wo sheng ming\u00a0: \"Ai he gan xie\" de xin qing ke yi chuan zao ji ji de neng liang) (in Chinese). Taibei Xian Xindian Shi. 2006. <nowiki>ISBN 9789576864971</nowiki>.\n* English edition: The Miracle of Water. New York; Hillsboro, OR: Atria: Beyond Words. 2007. <nowiki>ISBN 9781582701622</nowiki>.\n* Water Crystal Healing: Music & Images to Restore Your Well Being. New York; Hillsboro, OR: Atria: Beyond Words. 2006. <nowiki>ISBN 9781582701561</nowiki>.\n* The True Power of Water (Book): Healing and Discovering Ourselves; Beyond Words Pub., 2005. <nowiki>ISBN 9781582701288</nowiki>.<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n*\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name              = The Hidden Messages in Water\n| image             = The_hidden_message_in_water.png\n| author            = [[Masaru Emoto]]\n| country           = United States\n| language          = English\n| genre             = Body Mind & Spirit; Pseudoscience\n| publisher         = Beyond Words Pub.\n| release_date      = 2004\n| media_type        = Print\n| pages             = 159\n| isbn              = 978-1-58-270114-1\n}}\n\n== Introduction ==\n[[The Hidden Messages In Water|''The Hidden Messages In Water'']] is a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times Bestseller]] book, written by [[Masaru Emoto]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Hidden-Messages-in-Water/Masaru-Emoto/9780743289801|title=Hidden Messages in Water|date=2005-09-20|isbn=978-0-7432-8980-1|language=en}}</ref>. The book was published in the year 2005 and focuses on a [[pseudoscience]] hypotheses that the molecular structure of water changes by the presence of [[human consciousness]] nearby<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.redorbit.com/news/science/1144934/masaru_emotos_wonderful_world_of_water/|title=Masaru Emoto's Wonderful World of Water|date=2007-11-15|website=Redorbit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>. The book has therefore been translated into twenty four languages<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.co.uk/books/The-Hidden-Messages-in-Water/Masaru-Emoto/9781451656855|title=The Hidden Messages in Water|date=2011-07-05|isbn=978-1-4516-5685-5|language=en}}</ref>.\n\n==Background==\n\n[[Masaru Emoto]] was a Japanese author who broached the theory of a change in the molecular structure of water as a result of human\u2019s subconscious or conscious thoughts. Emoto made use of articulate experiments and diagrams to back his theory. Many researchers like biologist Tyler Volk, physician Harriet A. Hall<ref name=\":0\" />, and biochemist William Reville have often claimed that Emoto\u2019s findings fall under the Pseudoscience dynamic, a branch of science which has not found much validation from the prudent minds<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/the-pseudoscience-of-creating-beautiful-or-ugly-water-1.574583|title=The pseudoscience of creating beautiful (or ugly) water|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>. Masaru Emoto has also been regarded as the \u2018Doctor of alternative medicine\u2019 by some sources<ref name=\":1\" />.\n\n==Content==\n\nEmoto has used high speed photography and carefully propounded diagrammatic representation to elucidate the crystal formation in frozen water contingent on the nature of thoughts, the water was exposed to<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyom.com/cgi-bin/display/librarydisplay.cgi?lid=301|title=DailyOM - The Hidden Messages in Water by Masaru Emoto|website=www.dailyom.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>. The experiments presented in the book talks about formation of clear and snowflake shaped crystals in water which was claimed to be exposed to positive and lovable thoughts<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Radin|first=Dean|last2=Hayssen|first2=Gail|last3=Emoto|first3=Masaru|last4=Kizu|first4=Takashige|date=2006-09-01|title=Double-Blind Test of the Effects of Distant Intention on Water Crystal Formation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1550830706003272|journal=EXPLORE|language=en|volume=2|issue=5|pages=408\u2013411|doi=10.1016/j.explore.2006.06.004|issn=1550-8307}}</ref>. On the contrary, Emoto claims that crystal formation in water which was exposed to negative and abominable thoughts exhibited an asymmetric and unruly pattern. The book tries to suggest the idea that water might be highly reflective of its surroundings and could be used to impart health and positivity around<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.storytel.com/in/en/books/80391-The-Hidden-Messages-in-Water|title=The Hidden Messages in Water|website=www.storytel.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>.\n==Reception==\n\nThe book received a rather mixed attention. Some people hailed the findings demonstrated in the book and spoke greatly about its relevance. \u201cThe Hidden Messages in Water is magnificent. Through his genius photography and superb scientific skill, Dr. Masaru Emoto has created a book that is truly a mystical treasure.\u201d Said Caroline M. Myss, author of Sacred Contracts and Anatomy of the Spirit. Whereas, Stephen Kiesling in Spirituality & Health Magazine wrote \"What he is saying has nothing to do with science as I know it.\" And \"Perhaps Emoto is an evangelist who values the message of his images more than the particulars of science; nevertheless, this spiritual teacher might focus his future practice less on gratitude and more on honesty\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spirituality-health.com/articles-latest-message-water-dr-emoto-spiritual-madoff/|title=Latest Message from Water: Is Dr. Emoto a Spiritual Madoff? {{!}} Spirituality & Health|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>. Noelle C. Nelson, PhD and co-author of The Power of Appreciation said that \u201cDr. Emoto's work with water beautifully illustrates the healing power of love and gratitude.\u201d On being New York Times Bestseller, literary critic Dwight Garner wrote in The New York Times Book Review that \u201cit was one of those \u201chead-scratchers\" that made him question the sanity of the reading public.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/463050722|title=Want rain? It's all in the brain, expert says|last=Previch|first=Chad|date=January 21, 2006|website=ProQuest|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Critical reception and skepticism ==\nEmoto\u2019s work has managed to attract a lot of skepticism and critique. His work has shown considerable imprints of Pseudoscience and hence the credibility of his claims are constantly under question by the scientific community. According to a report published in \u201cit is very unlikely that there is any reality behind Emoto\u2019s claims. A triple blind study of these claims failed to show any effect. Also, the phenomenon he describes has never been published in a peer reviewed science journal, which almost certainly means that the effect cannot be demonstrated under controlled conditions.\u201d<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/the-pseudoscience-of-creating-beautiful-or-ugly-water-1.574583|title=The pseudoscience of creating beautiful (or ugly) water|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Skeptics also believe that The Hidden Messages in Water appeals to that class of people who get fascinated by \u201cnew age science\u201d like out of body experience and Chakra healing. There apparently is a huge fan base for these theories said William revile who is a professor of biochemistry at UCC.<ref name=\":2\" /><br />\n\n== More from the Author ==\n\n* \u6c34\u304b\u3089\u306e\u4f1d\u8a00: \u4e16\u754c\u521d!! \u6c34\u306e\u7d50\u6676\u5199\u771f\u96c6 (Mizu kara no dengon: sekaihatsu!! mizu no kessh\u014d shashinsh\u016b) [Messages from Water] (in Japanese). 1. Tokyo: Hado. 1999. <nowiki>ISBN 9784939098000</nowiki>.\n* English edition: The Message from Water: The Message from Water is Telling Us to Take a Look at Ourselves. 1. Hado. 2000. <nowiki>ISBN 9784939098000</nowiki>.\n* \u6c34\u304b\u3089\u306e\u4f1d\u8a00\uff1a \u4e16\u754c\u521d\uff01\uff01\u6c34\u306e\u6c37\u7d50\u7d50\u6676\u5199\u771f\u96c6\u4eca\u65e5\u3082\u6c34\u306b\u3042\u308a\u304c\u3068\u3046 (Mizu kara no dengon: sekaihatsu!! mizu no kessh\u014d shashinsh\u016b) [The Messages from Water] (in Japanese). 2. Tokyo: Hado. 2001. <nowiki>ISBN 9784939098048</nowiki>.\n* English edition: The Message from Water. 2. Hado. 2001. <nowiki>ISBN 9784939098048</nowiki>.\n* \u6c34\u304c\u4f1d\u3048\u308b\u611b\u306e\u304b\u305f\u3061 (Mizu ga tsutaeru ai no katachi) (in Japanese). Tokyo: Tokuma Shoten. 2003. <nowiki>ISBN 9784198617509</nowiki>.\n* English edition: The Shape of Love: Discovering Who We Are, Where We Came From, and Where We are Going. New York: Doubleday. 2007. <nowiki>ISBN 9780385518376</nowiki>.\n* Love Thyself: The Message from Water III. Carlsbad, CA: Hay House. 2004. <nowiki>ISBN 9781401908997</nowiki>.\n* \u6c34\u53ef\u4ee5\u6539\u8b8a\u6211\u751f\u547d\u00a0: \"\u611b\u548c\u611f\u8b1d\"\u7684\u5fc3\u60c5\u53ef\u4ee5\u5275\u9020\u7a4d\u6975\u7684\u80fd\u91cf (Shui ke yi gai bian wo sheng ming\u00a0: \"Ai he gan xie\" de xin qing ke yi chuan zao ji ji de neng liang) (in Chinese). Taibei Xian Xindian Shi. 2006. <nowiki>ISBN 9789576864971</nowiki>.\n* English edition: The Miracle of Water. New York; Hillsboro, OR: Atria: Beyond Words. 2007. <nowiki>ISBN 9781582701622</nowiki>.\n* Water Crystal Healing: Music & Images to Restore Your Well Being. New York; Hillsboro, OR: Atria: Beyond Words. 2006. <nowiki>ISBN 9781582701561</nowiki>.\n* The True Power of Water (Book): Healing and Discovering Ourselves; Beyond Words Pub., 2005. <nowiki>ISBN 9781582701288</nowiki>.<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Subtle Art of Not Giving a Fuck, The}}\n[[Category:Self-help book stubs]]\n[[Category:Self-help books]]\n[[Category:2016 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:English-language books]]\n", "name_user": "Inkmesh", "label": "safe", "comment": "I have removed some irrelevant information from the bottom of the page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hidden_Messages_in_Water"}
{"title_page": "Uthama Raasa", "text_new": "{{short description|1993 film by Raj Kapoor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Uthama Raasa\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Raj Kapoor (Tamil film director)|Raj Kapoor]]\n| producer       = K. Balu\n| writer         = Raj Kapoor\n| starring       = [[Prabhu (actor)|Prabhu]]<br>[[Kushboo]]<br>[[Radha Ravi]]<br>[[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]]\n| music          = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cinematography = [[Velu Prabhakaran]]\n| editing        = Ganesh-Kumar\n| studio         = K. B. Films\n| distributor    = K. B. Films\n| released       = 14 April 1993\n| runtime        = 141 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Uthama Raasa''''' (Tamil: \u0b89\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bbe) ({{trans|Righteous King}}) is a 1993 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]] film directed by [[Raj Kapoor (Tamil film director)|Raj Kapoor]] and starring [[Prabhu (actor)|Prabhu]], [[Kushboo]], [[Radha Ravi]] and [[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]]. It was produced by K. Balu and has a musical score by [[Ilaiyaraaja]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spicyonion.com/movie/uthama-rasa/|title=Uthama Raasa|accessdate=2014-11-16|publisher=spicyonion.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gomolo.com/uthamarasa-movie/11702|title=Uthama Raasa|accessdate=2014-11-16|publisher=gomolo.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nFeud between Chinnaiya ([[Prabhu]]) and Parama Thevar ([[Radha Ravi]]) has not eased up in 18 years. In his teenage years, Chinnaiya had cut the hands of Parama Thevar, for killing Chinnaiya's father, which is witnessed by Parama Thevar's daughter ([[Vaishnavi (Malayali actress)|Vaishnavi]]). This results in his daughter having a trauma of blood, and all her marriage alliances are not positive due to this.\n\nHere comes Meenakshi alias Meenu ([[Kushboo]]), who is Chinnaiya's cousin, completing her studies in the city. Both of them are in love since young, but do not tell each other. Marudhu([[Raja]]), son of Parama Thevar falls for Meenu's beauty. Marudhu takes pictures of Meenu, thinking of her. Once during a village festival, Chinnaiya fights with Marudhu which results in Meenu accusing Chinnaiya. But soon, they reconcile.\n\nMeenu's friends come from twin to bring her to a wedding. Before they leave with her, they manipulate Meenu to put up a drama with Chinnaiya for fun. Though reluctant, Meenu agrees. She falsely tells Chinnaiya that she is in love with a guy much to Chinnaiya's disappointment. At that moment, his mother, aatha ([[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]]), goes to fix alliance for Chinnaiya and Meenu.\n\nChinnaiya spots Meenu and Marudhu together, which happened to be an accidental meeting. He mistakes them to be a couple and thinks Meenu is in love with Marudhu. This worsens after he sees pictures of Meenu taken by Marudhu. Meenu, feeling guilty and unable to open up to her uncle, gives him an envelope with Chinnaiya's photo in it. She tells him that she is in love with the person in the photograph and cannot life without him. She leaves for the wedding and Chinnaiya thinks that it is picture of Marudhu.\n\nWithout his mother's knowledge and forgetting the enmity between Parama, goes to fix alliance for Meenu's sake. There, Parama asks Chinnaiya to marry his daughter, to which he agrees. Meenu comes back and gets shocked. She thereafter, tries to change Chinnaiya's mind, who on the other hand, a honest keeper.\n\nParama had actually planned to take all of Meenu's property and chase her out of the house, and kill Chinnaiya before his wedding with his daughter. Parama's mother, ([[S.N. Lakshmi]]) over hears this. He kills his mother later.\n\nParama's daughter later comes to know the truth about Meenu and Chinnaiya. She tells her father and Marudhu gets heartbroken. Parama vows revenge. When Chinnaiya's mother comes to break the alliance, Parama humiliated her by making his men walk naked around her. Angered, Chinnaiya goes to kill Parama and on the way, spots Parama's daughter married to Chinnaiya's servant ([[Charle]]). Marudhu gives up his love.\n\nOnce again humiliated, Parama decides to kill Chinnaiya and to marry Meenu. Chinnaiya rescues Meenu, and marries her in front of Parama. The villagers gather and plan to bury Parama alive, for all his misdeeds. Chinnaiya intervenes and tells the villagers that Parama's punishment is his life from that moment on. As the villagers make a move, Parama takes a sickle to kill Chinnaiya, but he is killed by Marudhu.\n\nThe film ends with Chinnaiya and Meenu, leading a happy life.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Prabhu (actor)|Prabhu]] as Chinnaiya<ref name=ie />\n* [[Kushboo]] as Meenakshi<ref name=ie />\n* [[Radha Ravi]] as Parama Thevar<ref name=ie />\n* [[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]] as Marudhu<ref name=ie />\n* [[Goundamani]] as Vellaiyangiri\n* [[Senthil]] as Vellayathevan\n* [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]]\n* [[Thyagu (actor)|Thyagu]]\n* [[Charle]]\n* [[Vaishnavi (Malayali actress)|Vaishnavi]] as Mangai<ref name=ie />\n* [[S. N. Lakshmi]]\n* Sethu Vinayagam\n* Senthamarai\n* Venkatesh\n* Boobathi Raja\n* Manikkaraj\n* Durga\n* Shanthi\n* Chandrika\n* Bindhu\n* Pandiyan\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe music was composed by [[Ilaiyaraaja]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://play.raaga.com/tamil/album/Uthama-Raasa-T0002993|title=Uthama Raasa Songs|accessdate=2014-12-16|publisher=raaga.com}}</ref>\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCF\" align=\"center\"\n| '''No.''' || '''Song''' || '''Singers''' ||'''Lyrics''' || '''Length (m:ss)'''\n|-\n| 1 || \"Intha Maamanoda\" || [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], [[S. Janaki]] || [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]] || 04:51\n|-\n| 2 || \"Nalla Neram\" || S. P. Balasubrahmanyam || [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]] || 05:09\n|-\n| 3 || \"Nandri Unakku\" || [[Malaysia Vasudevan]] || Vaali || 05:54\n|-\n| 4 || \"Paavalaru Pattu\" || [[Mano (singer)|Mano]] || Vaali || 05:04\n|-\n| 5 || \"Unna Maathi Paakkaamal\" || S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, S. Janaki || Vaali || 05:06\n|-\n| 6 || \"Vaaya Vaaya\" || S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, S. Janaki || Vaali || 05:09\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n''The Indian Express'' wrote \"Lovely music, good camerawork, fine performance by the lead pair [..] make the film an entertainer\".<ref name=ie>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19930430&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|title=Engrossing|website=The Indian Express|last=Mannath|first=Malini|date=April 30, 1993}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|id=42Amh4tVk4E|title=Uthama Raasa}}\n\n[[Category:1993 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Tamil film scores by Ilaiyaraaja]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1993 film by Raj Kapoor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Uthama Raasa\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Raj Kapoor (Tamil film director)|Raj Kapoor]]\n| producer       = K. Balu\n| writer         = Raj Kapoor\n| starring       = [[Prabhu (actor)|Prabhu]]<br>[[Kushboo]]<br>[[Radha Ravi]]<br>[[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]]\n| music          = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cinematography = [[Velu Prabhakaran]]\n| editing        = Ganesh-Kumar\n| studio         = K. B. Films\n| distributor    = K. B. Films\n| released       = 14 April 1993\n| runtime        = 141 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Uthama Raasa''''' (Tamil: \u0b89\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bbe) ({{trans|Righteous King}}) is a 1993 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]] film directed by [[Raj Kapoor (Tamil film director)|Raj Kapoor]] and starring [[Prabhu (actor)|Prabhu]], [[Kushboo]], [[Radha Ravi]] and [[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]]. It was produced by K. Balu and has a musical score by [[Ilaiyaraaja]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spicyonion.com/movie/uthama-rasa/|title=Uthama Raasa|accessdate=2014-11-16|publisher=spicyonion.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gomolo.com/uthamarasa-movie/11702|title=Uthama Raasa|accessdate=2014-11-16|publisher=gomolo.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nFeud between Chinnaiya ([[Prabhu]]) and Parama Thevar ([[Radha Ravi]]) has not eased up in 18 years. In his teenage years, Chinnaiya had cut the hands of Parama Thevar, for killing Chinnaiya's father, which is witnessed by Parama Thevar's daughter ([[Vaishnavi (Malayali actress)|Vaishnavi]]). This results in his daughter having a trauma of blood, and all her marriage alliances are not positive due to this.\n\nHere comes Meenakshi alias Meenu ([[Kushboo]]), who is Chinnaiya's cousin, completing her studies in the city. Both of them are in love since young, but do not tell each other. Marudhu([[Raja]]), son of Parama Thevar falls for Meenu's beauty. Marudhu takes pictures of Meenu, thinking of her. Once during a village festival, Chinnaiya fights with Marudhu which results in Meenu accusing Chinnaiya. But soon, they reconcile.\n\nMeenu's friends come from twin to bring her to a wedding. Before they leave with her, they manipulate Meenu to put up a drama with Chinnaiya for fun. Though reluctant, Meenu agrees. She falsely tells Chinnaiya that she is in love with a guy much to Chinnaiya's disappointment. At that moment, his mother, aatha ([[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]]), goes to fix alliance for Chinnaiya and Meenu.\n\nChinnaiya spots Meenu and Marudhu together, which happened to be an accidental meeting. He mistakes them to be a couple and thinks Meenu is in love with Marudhu. This worsens after he sees pictures of Meenu taken by Marudhu. Meenu, feeling guilty and unable to open up to her uncle, gives him an envelope with Chinnaiya's photo in it. She tells him that she is in love with the person in the photograph and cannot life without him. She leaves for the wedding and Chinnaiya thinks that it is picture of Marudhu.\n\nWithout his mother's knowledge and forgetting the enmity between Parama, goes to fix alliance for Meenu's sake. There, Parama asks Chinnaiya to marry his daughter, to which he agrees. Meenu comes back and gets shocked. She thereafter, tries to change Chinnaiya's mind, who on the other hand, a honest keeper.\n\nParama had actually planned to take all of Meenu's property and chase her out of the house, and kill Chinnaiya before his wedding with his daughter. Parama's mother, ([[S.N. Lakshmi]]) over hears this. He kills his mother later.\n\nParama's daughter later comes to know the truth about Meenu and Chinnaiya. She tells her father and Marudhu gets heartbroken. Parama vows revenge. When Chinnaiya's mother comes to break the alliance, Parama humiliated her by making his men walk naked around her. Angered, Chinnaiya goes to kill Parama and on the way, spots Parama's daughter married to Chinnaiya's servant ([[Charle]]). Marudhu gives up his love.\n\nOnce again humiliated, Parama decides to kill Chinnaiya and get married to Meenu. Chinnaiya rescues Meenu, and marries her in front of Parama. The villagers gather and plan to bury Parama alive, for all his misdeeds. Chinnaiya intervenes and tells the villagers that Parama's punishment is his life from that moment on. As the villagers make a move, Parama takes a sickle to kill Chinnaiya, but he is killed by Marudhu.\n\nThe film ends with Chinnaiya and Meenu, leading a happy life.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Prabhu (actor)|Prabhu]] as Chinnaiya<ref name=ie />\n* [[Kushboo]] as Meenakshi<ref name=ie />\n* [[Radha Ravi]] as Parama Thevar<ref name=ie />\n* [[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]] as Marudhu<ref name=ie />\n* [[Goundamani]] as Vellaiyangiri\n* [[Senthil]] as Vellayathevan\n* [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]]\n* [[Thyagu (actor)|Thyagu]]\n* [[Charle]]\n* [[Vaishnavi (Malayali actress)|Vaishnavi]] as Mangai<ref name=ie />\n* [[S. N. Lakshmi]]\n* Sethu Vinayagam\n* Senthamarai\n* Venkatesh\n* Boobathi Raja\n* Manikkaraj\n* Durga\n* Shanthi\n* Chandrika\n* Bindhu\n* Pandiyan\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe music was composed by [[Ilaiyaraaja]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://play.raaga.com/tamil/album/Uthama-Raasa-T0002993|title=Uthama Raasa Songs|accessdate=2014-12-16|publisher=raaga.com}}</ref>\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCF\" align=\"center\"\n| '''No.''' || '''Song''' || '''Singers''' ||'''Lyrics''' || '''Length (m:ss)'''\n|-\n| 1 || \"Intha Maamanoda\" || [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], [[S. Janaki]] || [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]] || 04:51\n|-\n| 2 || \"Nalla Neram\" || S. P. Balasubrahmanyam || [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]] || 05:09\n|-\n| 3 || \"Nandri Unakku\" || [[Malaysia Vasudevan]] || Vaali || 05:54\n|-\n| 4 || \"Paavalaru Pattu\" || [[Mano (singer)|Mano]] || Vaali || 05:04\n|-\n| 5 || \"Unna Maathi Paakkaamal\" || S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, S. Janaki || Vaali || 05:06\n|-\n| 6 || \"Vaaya Vaaya\" || S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, S. Janaki || Vaali || 05:09\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n''The Indian Express'' wrote \"Lovely music, good camerawork, fine performance by the lead pair [..] make the film an entertainer\".<ref name=ie>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19930430&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|title=Engrossing|website=The Indian Express|last=Mannath|first=Malini|date=April 30, 1993}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|id=42Amh4tVk4E|title=Uthama Raasa}}\n\n[[Category:1993 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Tamil film scores by Ilaiyaraaja]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label